{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1782532274004,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c7affeFPHv9jEwltlvKr","part":{"id":"prt_f0733f753001cm7etiNIkP7YgP","messageID":"msg_f0733f1ae001lQSXfKTffNe8CR","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c7affeFPHv9jEwltlvKr","snapshot":"ab87b191cf288cd2cf6e378b1a7cd773ba95a6e3","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"text","timestamp":1782532294698,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c7affeFPHv9jEwltlvKr","part":{"id":"prt_f07340a0a001pqpbIJETlEzegT","messageID":"msg_f0733f1ae001lQSXfKTffNe8CR","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c7affeFPHv9jEwltlvKr","type":"text","text":"Prior corpus already shows the interface expansion work has largely landed: the interface packet now has the shared register, brief dials, mechanical/content gates, real-UI loop, MCP reference routing, and a preflight card. Next I’m checking whether the remaining improvement opportunities are behavioral, routing, or validation gaps rather than more asset bulk.","time":{"start":1782532278794,"end":1782532294697},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"msg_014eb9dfa2151398016a3f48b6c1d88191a5d9e9e44e9597f6","phase":"commentary"}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532294749,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c7affeFPHv9jEwltlvKr","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_Xkn6fA9o7wfFlENcqiq88Ots","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/references/design-process/design_principles.md","offset":1,"limit":500},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/references/design-process/design_principles.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"Interface Design Principles\"\n3: description: \"Aesthetic direction for distinctive, intentional UI: grounding in the subject, palette and typography choices, deliberate motion, restraint, self-critique, and interface writing.\"\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"distinctive visual design\"\n6:   - \"avoid templated default look\"\n7:   - \"typography palette layout direction\"\n8:   - \"design plan and critique\"\n9:   - \"interface copy and writing\"\n10: importance_tier: normal\n11: contextType: implementation\n12: version: 1.5.0.3\n13: ---\n14: \n15: # Interface Design Principles\n16: \n17: Guidance for distinctive, intentional visual design when building or reshaping UI. Adapted verbatim from Anthropic's `frontend-design` skill (Apache-2.0, see `../../LICENSE.txt`).\n18: \n19: ---\n20: \n21: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n22: \n23: ### Core Principle\n24: Make deliberate, opinionated choices specific to the brief, and take one real aesthetic risk you can justify. A design that reads as a templated default has failed.\n25: \n26: ### When to Use\n27: - Building new UI, or reshaping an existing one, where the look should feel distinctive.\n28: - Choosing palette, typography, layout, motion, and interface copy.\n29: - Critiquing a design plan before writing code.\n30: \n31: ### The Studio Framing\n32: Approach this as the design lead at a small studio known for giving every client a visual identity that could not be mistaken for anyone else's. This client has already rejected proposals that felt templated, and is paying for a distinctive point of view: make deliberate, opinionated choices about palette, typography, and layout that are specific to this brief, and take one real aesthetic risk you can justify.\n33: \n34: ---\n35: \n36: ## 2. GROUND IT IN THE SUBJECT\n37: \n38: If the brief does not pin down what the product or subject is, pin it yourself before designing: name one concrete subject, its audience, and the page's single job, and state your choice. If there's any information in your memory about the human's preferences, context about what they're building, or designs you've made before – use that as a hint. The subject's own world, its materials, instruments, artifacts, and vernacular, is where distinctive choices come from. Build with the brief's real content and subject matter throughout.\n39: \n40: ---\n41: \n42: ## 3. DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n43: \n44: For web designs, the hero is a thesis. Open with the most characteristic thing in the subject's world, in whatever form makes sense for it: a headline, an image, an animation, a live demo, an interactive moment. Be deliberate with your choice: a big number with a small label, supporting stats, and a gradient accent is the template answer, only use if that's truly the best option.\n45: \n46: Typography carries the personality of the page. Pair the display and body faces deliberately, not the same families you would reach for on any other project, and set a clear type scale with intentional weights, widths, and spacing. Make the type treatment itself a memorable part of the design, not a neutral delivery vehicle for the content.\n47: \n48: Structure is information. Structural devices, numbering, eyebrows, dividers, labels, should encode something true about the content, not decorate it. Many generic designs use numbered markers (01 / 02 / 03), but that's only appropriate if the content actually is a sequence - like a real process or a typed timeline where order carries information the reader needs. Question if choices like numbered markers actually make sense before incorporating them.\n49: \n50: Use motion deliberately. Think about where and if animation can serve the subject: a page-load sequence, a scroll-triggered reveal, hover micro-interactions, ambient atmosphere. An orchestrated moment usually lands harder than scattered effects, so choose what the direction calls for. However, sometimes less is more, and extra animation contributes to the feeling that the design is AI-generated.\n51: \n52: Match complexity to the vision. Maximalist directions need elaborate execution. Minimal directions need precision in spacing, type, and detail. Elegance is executing the chosen vision well.\n53: \n54: Consider written content carefully. Often a design brief may not contain real content, and it's up to you to come up with copy. Copy can make a design feel as templated as the design itself. See Section 6 for more guidance.\n55: \n56: ---\n57: \n58: ## 4. PROCESS: BRAINSTORM, EXPLORE, PLAN, CRITIQUE, BUILD, CRITIQUE AGAIN\n59: \n60: For calibration: AI-generated design right now clusters around three looks. (1) A warm cream background (near #F4F1EA) with a high-contrast serif display and a terracotta accent. (2) A near-black background with a single bright acid-green or vermilion accent. (3) A broadsheet-style layout with hairline rules, zero border-radius, and dense newspaper-like columns. All three are legitimate for some briefs, but they are defaults rather than choices, and they appear regardless of subject. Where the brief pins down a visual direction, follow it exactly: the brief's own words always win, including when it asks for one of these looks. Where it leaves an axis free, don't spend that freedom on one of these defaults. Just like a human designer who's hired, there's often a careful balance between doing what you're good at and taking each project as a chance to experiment and learn.\n61: \n62: Work in two passes. First, brainstorm a short design plan based on the human's design brief: create a compact token system with color, type, layout, and signature. Color: describe the palette as 4–6 named hex values. Type: the typefaces for 2+ roles (a characterful display face that's used with restraint, a complementary body face, and a utility face for captions or data if needed). Layout: a layout concept, using one-sentence prose descriptions and ASCII wireframes to ideate and compare. Signature: the single unique element this page will be remembered by that embodies the brief in an appropriate way.\n63: \n64: Then review that plan against the brief before building: if any part of it reads like the generic default you would produce for any similar page (work through a similar prompt to see if you arrive somewhere similar) rather than a choice made for this specific brief, revise that part, say what you changed and why. Only after you've confirmed the relative uniqueness of your design plan should you start to write the code, following the revised plan exactly and deriving every color and type decision from it.\n65: \n66: When writing the code, be careful of structuring your CSS selector specificities. It's easy to generate CSS classes that cancel each other out (especially with a type-based selector like .section and a element-based selector like .cta). This can happen often with paddings/margins between sections.\n67: \n68: Try to do a lot of this planning and iteration in your thinking, and only show ideas to the user when you have higher confidence it'll delight them.\n69: \n70: ---\n71: \n72: ## 5. RESTRAINT AND SELF-CRITIQUE\n73: \n74: Spend your boldness in one place. Let the signature element be the one memorable thing, keep everything around it quiet and disciplined, and cut any decoration that does not serve the brief. Not taking a risk can be a risk itself! Build to a quality floor without announcing it: responsive down to mobile, visible keyboard focus, reduced motion respected. Critique your own work as you build, taking screenshots if your environment supports it – a picture is worth 1000 tokens. Consider Chanel's advice: before leaving the house, take a look in the mirror and remove one accessory. Human creators have memory and always try to do something new, so if you have a space to quickly jot down notes about what you've tried, it can help you in future passes.\n75: \n76: ---\n77: \n78: ## 6. WRITING IN DESIGN\n79: \n80: Words appear in a design for one reason: to make it easier to understand, and therefore easier to use. They are design material, not decoration. Bring the same intentionality to copy that you would bring to spacing and color. Before writing anything, ask what the design needs to say, and how it can best be said to help the person navigate the experience.\n81: \n82: Write from the end user's side of the screen. Name things by what people control and recognize, never by how the system is built. A person manages notifications, not webhook config. Describe what something does in plain terms rather than selling it. Being specific is always better than being clever.\n83: \n84: Use active voice as default. A control should say exactly what happens when it's used: \"Save changes,\" not \"Submit.\" An action keeps the same name through the whole flow, so the button that says \"Publish\" produces a toast that says \"Published.\" The vocabulary of an interface is the signposting for someone navigating the product. Cohesion and consistency are how people learn their way around.\n85: \n86: Treat failure and emptiness as moments for direction, not mood. Explain what went wrong and how to fix it, in the interface's voice rather than a person's. Errors don't apologize, and they are never vague about what happened. An empty screen is an invitation to act.\n87: \n88: Keep the register conversational and tuned: plain verbs, sentence case, no filler, with tone matched to the brand and the audience. Let each element do exactly one job. A label labels, an example demonstrates, and nothing quietly does double duty.\n\n(End of file - total 88 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"Interface Design Principles\"\ndescription: \"Aesthetic direction for distinctive, intentional UI: grounding in the subject, palette and typography choices, deliberate motion, restraint, self-critique, and interface writing.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"distinctive visual design\"\n  - \"avoid templated default look\"\n  - \"typography palette layout direction\"\n  - \"design plan and critique\"\n  - \"interface copy and writing\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.5.0.3\n---\n\n# Interface Design Principles\n\nGuidance for distinctive, intentional visual design when building or reshaping UI. Adapted verbatim from Anthropic's `frontend-design` skill (Apache-2.0, see `../../LICENSE.txt`).\n\n---\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/references/design-process/design_principles.md","text":"---\ntitle: \"Interface Design Principles\"\ndescription: \"Aesthetic direction for distinctive, intentional UI: grounding in the subject, palette and typography choices, deliberate motion, restraint, self-critique, and interface writing.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"distinctive visual design\"\n  - \"avoid templated default look\"\n  - \"typography palette layout direction\"\n  - \"design plan and critique\"\n  - \"interface copy and writing\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.5.0.3\n---\n\n# Interface Design Principles\n\nGuidance for distinctive, intentional visual design when building or reshaping UI. Adapted verbatim from Anthropic's `frontend-design` skill (Apache-2.0, see `../../LICENSE.txt`).\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Core Principle\nMake deliberate, opinionated choices specific to the brief, and take one real aesthetic risk you can justify. A design that reads as a templated default has failed.\n\n### When to Use\n- Building new UI, or reshaping an existing one, where the look should feel distinctive.\n- Choosing palette, typography, layout, motion, and interface copy.\n- Critiquing a design plan before writing code.\n\n### The Studio Framing\nApproach this as the design lead at a small studio known for giving every client a visual identity that could not be mistaken for anyone else's. This client has already rejected proposals that felt templated, and is paying for a distinctive point of view: make deliberate, opinionated choices about palette, typography, and layout that are specific to this brief, and take one real aesthetic risk you can justify.\n\n---\n\n## 2. GROUND IT IN THE SUBJECT\n\nIf the brief does not pin down what the product or subject is, pin it yourself before designing: name one concrete subject, its audience, and the page's single job, and state your choice. If there's any information in your memory about the human's preferences, context about what they're building, or designs you've made before – use that as a hint. The subject's own world, its materials, instruments, artifacts, and vernacular, is where distinctive choices come from. Build with the brief's real content and subject matter throughout.\n\n---\n\n## 3. DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\nFor web designs, the hero is a thesis. Open with the most characteristic thing in the subject's world, in whatever form makes sense for it: a headline, an image, an animation, a live demo, an interactive moment. Be deliberate with your choice: a big number with a small label, supporting stats, and a gradient accent is the template answer, only use if that's truly the best option.\n\nTypography carries the personality of the page. Pair the display and body faces deliberately, not the same families you would reach for on any other project, and set a clear type scale with intentional weights, widths, and spacing. Make the type treatment itself a memorable part of the design, not a neutral delivery vehicle for the content.\n\nStructure is information. Structural devices, numbering, eyebrows, dividers, labels, should encode something true about the content, not decorate it. Many generic designs use numbered markers (01 / 02 / 03), but that's only appropriate if the content actually is a sequence - like a real process or a typed timeline where order carries information the reader needs. Question if choices like numbered markers actually make sense before incorporating them.\n\nUse motion deliberately. Think about where and if animation can serve the subject: a page-load sequence, a scroll-triggered reveal, hover micro-interactions, ambient atmosphere. An orchestrated moment usually lands harder than scattered effects, so choose what the direction calls for. However, sometimes less is more, and extra animation contributes to the feeling that the design is AI-generated.\n\nMatch complexity to the vision. Maximalist directions need elaborate execution. Minimal directions need precision in spacing, type, and detail. Elegance is executing the chosen vision well.\n\nConsider written content carefully. Often a design brief may not contain real content, and it's up to you to come up with copy. Copy can make a design feel as templated as the design itself. See Section 6 for more guidance.\n\n---\n\n## 4. PROCESS: BRAINSTORM, EXPLORE, PLAN, CRITIQUE, BUILD, CRITIQUE AGAIN\n\nFor calibration: AI-generated design right now clusters around three looks. (1) A warm cream background (near #F4F1EA) with a high-contrast serif display and a terracotta accent. (2) A near-black background with a single bright acid-green or vermilion accent. (3) A broadsheet-style layout with hairline rules, zero border-radius, and dense newspaper-like columns. All three are legitimate for some briefs, but they are defaults rather than choices, and they appear regardless of subject. Where the brief pins down a visual direction, follow it exactly: the brief's own words always win, including when it asks for one of these looks. Where it leaves an axis free, don't spend that freedom on one of these defaults. Just like a human designer who's hired, there's often a careful balance between doing what you're good at and taking each project as a chance to experiment and learn.\n\nWork in two passes. First, brainstorm a short design plan based on the human's design brief: create a compact token system with color, type, layout, and signature. Color: describe the palette as 4–6 named hex values. Type: the typefaces for 2+ roles (a characterful display face that's used with restraint, a complementary body face, and a utility face for captions or data if needed). Layout: a layout concept, using one-sentence prose descriptions and ASCII wireframes to ideate and compare. Signature: the single unique element this page will be remembered by that embodies the brief in an appropriate way.\n\nThen review that plan against the brief before building: if any part of it reads like the generic default you would produce for any similar page (work through a similar prompt to see if you arrive somewhere similar) rather than a choice made for this specific brief, revise that part, say what you changed and why. Only after you've confirmed the relative uniqueness of your design plan should you start to write the code, following the revised plan exactly and deriving every color and type decision from it.\n\nWhen writing the code, be careful of structuring your CSS selector specificities. It's easy to generate CSS classes that cancel each other out (especially with a type-based selector like .section and a element-based selector like .cta). This can happen often with paddings/margins between sections.\n\nTry to do a lot of this planning and iteration in your thinking, and only show ideas to the user when you have higher confidence it'll delight them.\n\n---\n\n## 5. RESTRAINT AND SELF-CRITIQUE\n\nSpend your boldness in one place. Let the signature element be the one memorable thing, keep everything around it quiet and disciplined, and cut any decoration that does not serve the brief. Not taking a risk can be a risk itself! Build to a quality floor without announcing it: responsive down to mobile, visible keyboard focus, reduced motion respected. Critique your own work as you build, taking screenshots if your environment supports it – a picture is worth 1000 tokens. Consider Chanel's advice: before leaving the house, take a look in the mirror and remove one accessory. Human creators have memory and always try to do something new, so if you have a space to quickly jot down notes about what you've tried, it can help you in future passes.\n\n---\n\n## 6. WRITING IN DESIGN\n\nWords appear in a design for one reason: to make it easier to understand, and therefore easier to use. They are design material, not decoration. Bring the same intentionality to copy that you would bring to spacing and color. Before writing anything, ask what the design needs to say, and how it can best be said to help the person navigate the experience.\n\nWrite from the end user's side of the screen. Name things by what people control and recognize, never by how the system is built. A person manages notifications, not webhook config. Describe what something does in plain terms rather than selling it. Being specific is always better than being clever.\n\nUse active voice as default. A control should say exactly what happens when it's used: \"Save changes,\" not \"Submit.\" An action keeps the same name through the whole flow, so the button that says \"Publish\" produces a toast that says \"Published.\" The vocabulary of an interface is the signposting for someone navigating the product. Cohesion and consistency are how people learn their way around.\n\nTreat failure and emptiness as moments for direction, not mood. Explain what went wrong and how to fix it, in the interface's voice rather than a person's. Errors don't apologize, and they are never vague about what happened. An empty screen is an invitation to act.\n\nKeep the register conversational and tuned: plain verbs, sentence case, no filler, with tone matched to the brand and the audience. Let each element do exactly one job. A label labels, an example demonstrates, and nothing quietly does double duty.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":88,"totalLines":88,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/references/design-process/design_principles.md","time":{"start":1782532294743,"end":1782532294747}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_014eb9dfa2151398016a3f48c6a7948191af411b760e6872e3"}},"id":"prt_f0734482b001LUU8PgeGhkIQHV","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c7affeFPHv9jEwltlvKr","messageID":"msg_f0733f1ae001lQSXfKTffNe8CR"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532294798,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c7affeFPHv9jEwltlvKr","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_Q1KjAQ5ioiXvhBBFPqlv4kIK","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/register.md","offset":1,"limit":400},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/register.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Brand-vs-Product Operating Register\n3: description: The shared sk-design operating register. Declare whether a design IS the product or SERVES it, then read the six downstream dials that decision sets.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"brand vs product register\"\n6:   - \"design operating register\"\n7:   - \"design is the product\"\n8:   - \"design serves the product\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: general\n11: version: 1.0.0.0\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Brand-vs-Product Operating Register\n15: \n16: The first design decision, before color, type, layout, or motion: is this surface a Brand surface or a Product surface? That one call sets six downstream dials. Skipping it is the most common reason design output drifts to a generic default.\n17: \n18: ---\n19: \n20: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n21: \n22: ### Purpose\n23: \n24: Give every design mode one shared, up-front decision that calibrates the rest of the work. \"Brand\" and \"Product\" are not styles, they are operating postures. The register names the posture once and the six dials inherit it, so a landing page and an admin dashboard never get the same defaults by accident.\n25: \n26: ### Usage\n27: \n28: Set the register at the start of any design task, before the mode-specific workflow runs. Each mode (interface, foundations, motion, audit, md-generator) reads the register and applies the dial settings for the chosen posture. The register is shared vocabulary, not a sixth mode and not a replacement for mode workflows.\n29: \n30: ---\n31: \n32: ## 2. THE REGISTER DECISION\n33: \n34: A surface takes one of two postures:\n35: \n36: - **Brand (design IS the product).** Marketing sites, landing pages, campaigns, long-form content, portfolios. The design is the thing being consumed, so expression, identity and a memorable moment are the job.\n37: - **Product (design SERVES the product).** App UI, admin, dashboards, tools, settings, forms. The design carries the user to a task, so clarity, density and consistency are the job.\n38: \n39: ### How to pick (first match wins)\n40: \n41: 1. **Task cue.** Words in the request like \"landing page\", \"campaign\" and \"portfolio\" point to Brand. Words like \"dashboard\", \"admin\", \"settings\" and \"tool\" point to Product.\n42: 2. **Surface in focus.** The actual page, route, or file being worked on, even inside a mixed app. A marketing page inside a product app is still Brand.\n43: 3. **Declared register.** A `register` field in the project's PRODUCT.md or DESIGN.md, when present, is authoritative.\n44: \n45: A mixed product has both postures: the marketing surface is Brand, the app shell is Product. Set the register per surface, not per project.\n46: \n47: ---\n48: \n49: ## 3. THE SIX DIALS\n50: \n51: The register sets these six. When the surface is unlabeled and internal, Product is the safer default. Brand is the default only when the surface is clearly the thing being sold.\n52: \n53: | Dial | Brand (design IS the product) | Product (design SERVES the product) |\n54: |---|---|---|\n55: | **Density** | Generous and expressive, with room for one big move | Information-dense and efficient, whitespace earns its place |\n56: | **Motion budget** | Motion is voice: one well-rehearsed entrance beats scattered reveals, with scroll motion reserved for moments that earn it | 150 to 250 ms state transitions only, no page-load choreography, motion conveys feedback, reveal, loading and view changes |\n57: | **Color dosage** | Palette is voice: Committed, Full, or Drenched strategies may exceed the 10% accent rule | Semantic-first and almost always Restrained, accent reserved for primary action, selection and state, never decoration |\n58: | **Copy register** | Expressive and voice-led, the words carry identity | Plain, functional and consistent, one copy register across every screen |\n59: | **Anti-slop strictness** | Reject the brand defaults: cream or sand body background, an eyebrow above every section, numbered section scaffolding, over-rounded cards | Reject the product defaults: low-contrast muted-gray text, color used as decoration, undifferentiated card grids |\n60: | **Audit severity** | Weight distinctiveness and voice, a generic-but-functional brand surface is a real finding | Weight affordance, accessibility and consistency, an expressive-but-unclear product surface is a real finding |\n61: \n62: ### The color-strategy axis\n63: \n64: Color dosage resolves to one of four strategies, ordered by how much color carries the surface:\n65: \n66: - **Restrained**: tinted neutrals plus one accent at 10% or less. The Product default.\n67: - **Committed**: one saturated color carries 30 to 60% of the surface. The Brand default for identity-driven pages.\n68: - **Full palette**: three to four named color roles, each used deliberately. Brand campaigns and Product data visualization.\n69: - **Drenched**: the surface itself is the color. Brand heroes and campaign pages only.\n70: \n71: ---\n72: \n73: ## 4. MODE USAGE\n74: \n75: - **interface** reads the register first, then sets density, the motion budget and the color strategy for direction and build.\n76: - **foundations** reads the register to choose the color strategy and the density of the token system (spacing rhythm, type scale).\n77: - **motion** reads the motion-budget dial to decide whether a surface gets choreography or only state transitions.\n78: - **audit** reads the audit-severity dial so a finding is weighted by posture: distinctiveness for Brand, affordance and consistency for Product.\n79: - **md-generator** records the register of the site it extracts, so a captured Style Reference carries the posture forward.\n\n(End of file - total 79 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Brand-vs-Product Operating Register\ndescription: The shared sk-design operating register. Declare whether a design IS the product or SERVES it, then read the six downstream dials that decision sets.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"brand vs product register\"\n  - \"design operating register\"\n  - \"design is the product\"\n  - \"design serves the product\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Brand-vs-Product Operating Register\n\nThe first design decision, before color, type, layout, or motion: is this surface a Brand surface or a Product surface? That one call sets six downstream dials. Skipping it is the most common reason design output drifts to a generic default.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/register.md","text":"---\ntitle: Brand-vs-Product Operating Register\ndescription: The shared sk-design operating register. Declare whether a design IS the product or SERVES it, then read the six downstream dials that decision sets.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"brand vs product register\"\n  - \"design operating register\"\n  - \"design is the product\"\n  - \"design serves the product\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: general\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Brand-vs-Product Operating Register\n\nThe first design decision, before color, type, layout, or motion: is this surface a Brand surface or a Product surface? That one call sets six downstream dials. Skipping it is the most common reason design output drifts to a generic default.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nGive every design mode one shared, up-front decision that calibrates the rest of the work. \"Brand\" and \"Product\" are not styles, they are operating postures. The register names the posture once and the six dials inherit it, so a landing page and an admin dashboard never get the same defaults by accident.\n\n### Usage\n\nSet the register at the start of any design task, before the mode-specific workflow runs. Each mode (interface, foundations, motion, audit, md-generator) reads the register and applies the dial settings for the chosen posture. The register is shared vocabulary, not a sixth mode and not a replacement for mode workflows.\n\n---\n\n## 2. THE REGISTER DECISION\n\nA surface takes one of two postures:\n\n- **Brand (design IS the product).** Marketing sites, landing pages, campaigns, long-form content, portfolios. The design is the thing being consumed, so expression, identity and a memorable moment are the job.\n- **Product (design SERVES the product).** App UI, admin, dashboards, tools, settings, forms. The design carries the user to a task, so clarity, density and consistency are the job.\n\n### How to pick (first match wins)\n\n1. **Task cue.** Words in the request like \"landing page\", \"campaign\" and \"portfolio\" point to Brand. Words like \"dashboard\", \"admin\", \"settings\" and \"tool\" point to Product.\n2. **Surface in focus.** The actual page, route, or file being worked on, even inside a mixed app. A marketing page inside a product app is still Brand.\n3. **Declared register.** A `register` field in the project's PRODUCT.md or DESIGN.md, when present, is authoritative.\n\nA mixed product has both postures: the marketing surface is Brand, the app shell is Product. Set the register per surface, not per project.\n\n---\n\n## 3. THE SIX DIALS\n\nThe register sets these six. When the surface is unlabeled and internal, Product is the safer default. Brand is the default only when the surface is clearly the thing being sold.\n\n| Dial | Brand (design IS the product) | Product (design SERVES the product) |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Density** | Generous and expressive, with room for one big move | Information-dense and efficient, whitespace earns its place |\n| **Motion budget** | Motion is voice: one well-rehearsed entrance beats scattered reveals, with scroll motion reserved for moments that earn it | 150 to 250 ms state transitions only, no page-load choreography, motion conveys feedback, reveal, loading and view changes |\n| **Color dosage** | Palette is voice: Committed, Full, or Drenched strategies may exceed the 10% accent rule | Semantic-first and almost always Restrained, accent reserved for primary action, selection and state, never decoration |\n| **Copy register** | Expressive and voice-led, the words carry identity | Plain, functional and consistent, one copy register across every screen |\n| **Anti-slop strictness** | Reject the brand defaults: cream or sand body background, an eyebrow above every section, numbered section scaffolding, over-rounded cards | Reject the product defaults: low-contrast muted-gray text, color used as decoration, undifferentiated card grids |\n| **Audit severity** | Weight distinctiveness and voice, a generic-but-functional brand surface is a real finding | Weight affordance, accessibility and consistency, an expressive-but-unclear product surface is a real finding |\n\n### The color-strategy axis\n\nColor dosage resolves to one of four strategies, ordered by how much color carries the surface:\n\n- **Restrained**: tinted neutrals plus one accent at 10% or less. The Product default.\n- **Committed**: one saturated color carries 30 to 60% of the surface. The Brand default for identity-driven pages.\n- **Full palette**: three to four named color roles, each used deliberately. Brand campaigns and Product data visualization.\n- **Drenched**: the surface itself is the color. Brand heroes and campaign pages only.\n\n---\n\n## 4. MODE USAGE\n\n- **interface** reads the register first, then sets density, the motion budget and the color strategy for direction and build.\n- **foundations** reads the register to choose the color strategy and the density of the token system (spacing rhythm, type scale).\n- **motion** reads the motion-budget dial to decide whether a surface gets choreography or only state transitions.\n- **audit** reads the audit-severity dial so a finding is weighted by posture: distinctiveness for Brand, affordance and consistency for Product.\n- **md-generator** records the register of the site it extracts, so a captured Style Reference carries the posture forward.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":79,"totalLines":79,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/shared/register.md","time":{"start":1782532294794,"end":1782532294797}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_014eb9dfa2151398016a3f48c6a7b4819190fd4cd43002fcd3"}},"id":"prt_f07344871001zjHuaXnYDJIaqB","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c7affeFPHv9jEwltlvKr","messageID":"msg_f0733f1ae001lQSXfKTffNe8CR"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532294864,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c7affeFPHv9jEwltlvKr","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_IoMjOHauszWDTcvpMU065Yz1","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/mode-registry.json","offset":1,"limit":400},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/mode-registry.json</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: {\n2:   \"skill\": \"sk-design\",\n3:   \"version\": \"1.0.0\",\n4:   \"description\": \"Declarative mode registry: the single source of truth for the discriminator (workflowMode/backendKind) PLUS the advisorRouting projection for sk-design. The hub reads this file to resolve a mode; the advisor routes any design query to the single identity sk-design and the hub picks the mode. All five modes route by hub membership (routingClass 'metadata'), so there is no advisor map entry per mode and no merged-identity projection — the advisor does not read this file at runtime.\",\n5:   \"discriminator\": {\n6:     \"workflowMode\": \"Public hub/mode key. Stable identity used by the hub router and this registry. Carried by every mode.\",\n7:     \"backendKind\": \"Which backend runs the mode: reference-base (cites the shared design reference base under references/) or playwright-extract (runs the embedded Playwright CSS-extraction pipeline).\"\n8:   },\n9:   \"advisorRoutingContract\": {\n10:     \"routingClass\": \"How the advisor finds the mode. For sk-design every mode is 'metadata' = resolved by hub membership; the advisor routes the single identity sk-design and the hub picks the mode, so no mode carries an advisor map entry or a merged-identity projection.\",\n11:     \"packetSkillName\": \"The packet's SKILL.md name. The original flat skill name is preserved as packetSkillName; the packet folder is the short mode key, so folder != packetSkillName is grandfathered here and recorded per mode via grandfatheredFolderMismatch.\",\n12:     \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": \"true when the packet folder (short mode key, e.g. 'interface') differs from packetSkillName (the preserved flat name, e.g. 'interface'). All five sk-design modes preserve their original flat names, so all five are grandfathered.\"\n13:   },\n14:   \"modes\": [\n15:     {\n16:       \"workflowMode\": \"interface\",\n17:       \"backendKind\": \"reference-base\",\n18:       \"packet\": \"design-interface\",\n19:       \"packetSkillName\": \"design-interface\",\n20:       \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": false,\n21:       \"aliases\": [\"interface design\", \"frontend design\", \"visual design\", \"visual identity\", \"make it look good\", \"looks templated\", \"redesign the ui\", \"hero section\", \"ui build\", \"design variations\"],\n22:       \"advisorRouting\": {\n23:         \"routingClass\": \"metadata\",\n24:         \"packetSkillName\": \"design-interface\"\n25:       }\n26:     },\n27:     {\n28:       \"workflowMode\": \"foundations\",\n29:       \"backendKind\": \"reference-base\",\n30:       \"packet\": \"design-foundations\",\n31:       \"packetSkillName\": \"design-foundations\",\n32:       \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": false,\n33:       \"aliases\": [\"design foundations\", \"color system\", \"oklch palette\", \"color token system\", \"dark mode palette\", \"typography scale\", \"font pairing\", \"spacing system\", \"responsive layout\", \"design tokens\"],\n34:       \"advisorRouting\": {\n35:         \"routingClass\": \"metadata\",\n36:         \"packetSkillName\": \"design-foundations\"\n37:       }\n38:     },\n39:     {\n40:       \"workflowMode\": \"motion\",\n41:       \"backendKind\": \"reference-base\",\n42:       \"packet\": \"design-motion\",\n43:       \"packetSkillName\": \"design-motion\",\n44:       \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": false,\n45:       \"aliases\": [\"motion design\", \"animate this\", \"micro-interactions\", \"transitions\", \"AnimatePresence\", \"exit animation\", \"reduced motion\", \"morphing icons\", \"motion performance\"],\n46:       \"advisorRouting\": {\n47:         \"routingClass\": \"metadata\",\n48:         \"packetSkillName\": \"design-motion\"\n49:       }\n50:     },\n51:     {\n52:       \"workflowMode\": \"audit\",\n53:       \"backendKind\": \"reference-base\",\n54:       \"packet\": \"design-audit\",\n55:       \"packetSkillName\": \"design-audit\",\n56:       \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": false,\n57:       \"aliases\": [\"design audit\", \"ui critique\", \"accessibility audit\", \"performance audit\", \"anti-slop detection\", \"production hardening\", \"design quality score\", \"P0 P1 design findings\"],\n58:       \"advisorRouting\": {\n59:         \"routingClass\": \"metadata\",\n60:         \"packetSkillName\": \"design-audit\"\n61:       }\n62:     },\n63:     {\n64:       \"workflowMode\": \"md-generator\",\n65:       \"backendKind\": \"playwright-extract\",\n66:       \"packet\": \"design-md-generator\",\n67:       \"packetSkillName\": \"design-md-generator\",\n68:       \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": false,\n69:       \"aliases\": [\"extract design system\", \"generate design.md\", \"capture website css\", \"design tokens from url\", \"create design reference\", \"design-to-markdown\", \"extract design tokens\"],\n70:       \"advisorRouting\": {\n71:         \"routingClass\": \"metadata\",\n72:         \"packetSkillName\": \"design-md-generator\"\n73:       }\n74:     }\n75:   ]\n76: }\n\n(End of file - total 76 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\n  \"skill\": \"sk-design\",\n  \"version\": \"1.0.0\",\n  \"description\": \"Declarative mode registry: the single source of truth for the discriminator (workflowMode/backendKind) PLUS the advisorRouting projection for sk-design. The hub reads this file to resolve a mode; the advisor routes any design query to the single identity sk-design and the hub picks the mode. All five modes route by hub membership (routingClass 'metadata'), so there is no advisor map entry per mode and no merged-identity projection — the advisor does not read this file at runtime.\",\n  \"discriminator\": {\n    \"workflowMode\": \"Public hub/mode key. Stable identity used by the hub router and this registry. Carried by every mode.\",\n    \"backendKind\": \"Which backend runs the mode: reference-base (cites the shared design reference base under references/) or playwright-extract (runs the embedded Playwright CSS-extraction pipeline).\"\n  },\n  \"advisorRoutingContract\": {\n    \"routingClass\": \"How the advisor finds the mode. For sk-design every mode is 'metadata' = resolved by hub membership; the advisor routes the single identity sk-design and the hub picks the mode, so no mode carries an advisor map entry or a merged-identity projection.\",\n    \"packetSkillName\": \"The packet's SKILL.md name. The original flat skill name is preserved as packetSkillName; the packet folder is the short mode key, so folder != packetSkillName is grandfathered here and recorded per mode via grandfatheredFolderMismatch.\",\n    \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": \"true when the packet folder (short mode key, e.g. 'interface') differs from packetSkillName (the preserved flat name, e.g. 'interface'). All five sk-design modes preserve their original flat names, so all five are grandfathered.\"\n  },\n  \"modes\": [\n    {\n      \"workflowMode\": \"interface\",\n      \"backendKind\": \"reference-base\",\n      \"packet\": \"design-interface\",\n      \"packetSkillName\": \"design-interface\",\n      \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": false,","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/mode-registry.json","text":"{\n  \"skill\": \"sk-design\",\n  \"version\": \"1.0.0\",\n  \"description\": \"Declarative mode registry: the single source of truth for the discriminator (workflowMode/backendKind) PLUS the advisorRouting projection for sk-design. The hub reads this file to resolve a mode; the advisor routes any design query to the single identity sk-design and the hub picks the mode. All five modes route by hub membership (routingClass 'metadata'), so there is no advisor map entry per mode and no merged-identity projection — the advisor does not read this file at runtime.\",\n  \"discriminator\": {\n    \"workflowMode\": \"Public hub/mode key. Stable identity used by the hub router and this registry. Carried by every mode.\",\n    \"backendKind\": \"Which backend runs the mode: reference-base (cites the shared design reference base under references/) or playwright-extract (runs the embedded Playwright CSS-extraction pipeline).\"\n  },\n  \"advisorRoutingContract\": {\n    \"routingClass\": \"How the advisor finds the mode. For sk-design every mode is 'metadata' = resolved by hub membership; the advisor routes the single identity sk-design and the hub picks the mode, so no mode carries an advisor map entry or a merged-identity projection.\",\n    \"packetSkillName\": \"The packet's SKILL.md name. The original flat skill name is preserved as packetSkillName; the packet folder is the short mode key, so folder != packetSkillName is grandfathered here and recorded per mode via grandfatheredFolderMismatch.\",\n    \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": \"true when the packet folder (short mode key, e.g. 'interface') differs from packetSkillName (the preserved flat name, e.g. 'interface'). All five sk-design modes preserve their original flat names, so all five are grandfathered.\"\n  },\n  \"modes\": [\n    {\n      \"workflowMode\": \"interface\",\n      \"backendKind\": \"reference-base\",\n      \"packet\": \"design-interface\",\n      \"packetSkillName\": \"design-interface\",\n      \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": false,\n      \"aliases\": [\"interface design\", \"frontend design\", \"visual design\", \"visual identity\", \"make it look good\", \"looks templated\", \"redesign the ui\", \"hero section\", \"ui build\", \"design variations\"],\n      \"advisorRouting\": {\n        \"routingClass\": \"metadata\",\n        \"packetSkillName\": \"design-interface\"\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"workflowMode\": \"foundations\",\n      \"backendKind\": \"reference-base\",\n      \"packet\": \"design-foundations\",\n      \"packetSkillName\": \"design-foundations\",\n      \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": false,\n      \"aliases\": [\"design foundations\", \"color system\", \"oklch palette\", \"color token system\", \"dark mode palette\", \"typography scale\", \"font pairing\", \"spacing system\", \"responsive layout\", \"design tokens\"],\n      \"advisorRouting\": {\n        \"routingClass\": \"metadata\",\n        \"packetSkillName\": \"design-foundations\"\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"workflowMode\": \"motion\",\n      \"backendKind\": \"reference-base\",\n      \"packet\": \"design-motion\",\n      \"packetSkillName\": \"design-motion\",\n      \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": false,\n      \"aliases\": [\"motion design\", \"animate this\", \"micro-interactions\", \"transitions\", \"AnimatePresence\", \"exit animation\", \"reduced motion\", \"morphing icons\", \"motion performance\"],\n      \"advisorRouting\": {\n        \"routingClass\": \"metadata\",\n        \"packetSkillName\": \"design-motion\"\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"workflowMode\": \"audit\",\n      \"backendKind\": \"reference-base\",\n      \"packet\": \"design-audit\",\n      \"packetSkillName\": \"design-audit\",\n      \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": false,\n      \"aliases\": [\"design audit\", \"ui critique\", \"accessibility audit\", \"performance audit\", \"anti-slop detection\", \"production hardening\", \"design quality score\", \"P0 P1 design findings\"],\n      \"advisorRouting\": {\n        \"routingClass\": \"metadata\",\n        \"packetSkillName\": \"design-audit\"\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"workflowMode\": \"md-generator\",\n      \"backendKind\": \"playwright-extract\",\n      \"packet\": \"design-md-generator\",\n      \"packetSkillName\": \"design-md-generator\",\n      \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": false,\n      \"aliases\": [\"extract design system\", \"generate design.md\", \"capture website css\", \"design tokens from url\", \"create design reference\", \"design-to-markdown\", \"extract design tokens\"],\n      \"advisorRouting\": {\n        \"routingClass\": \"metadata\",\n        \"packetSkillName\": \"design-md-generator\"\n      }\n    }\n  ]\n}","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":76,"totalLines":76,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/mode-registry.json","time":{"start":1782532294861,"end":1782532294863}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_014eb9dfa2151398016a3f48c6a7c4819184a6c50028f4a2b5"}},"id":"prt_f0734488f0011kY2FZ8livZ4f5","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c7affeFPHv9jEwltlvKr","messageID":"msg_f0733f1ae001lQSXfKTffNe8CR"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532294912,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c7affeFPHv9jEwltlvKr","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_1GKRP8k2ghSER654bbmBggTw","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/assets/interface_preflight_card.md","offset":1,"limit":300},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/assets/interface_preflight_card.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"Interface Pre-Flight Card\"\n3: description: \"A mechanical fill-in pass/fail card to run on a built or planned interface before calling it done. Covers hero, bento, eyebrow and meta-label sweep, button contrast, breakpoint overflow, real imagery, copy audit, motion motivation, reduced motion, mobile collapse, and the AI-tell sweep. Every box is binary.\"\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"interface pre-flight card\"\n6:   - \"ui pass fail checklist\"\n7:   - \"design pre-flight gate\"\n8:   - \"ai tell sweep card\"\n9: importance_tier: normal\n10: contextType: implementation\n11: version: 1.0.0.0\n12: ---\n13: \n14: # Interface Pre-Flight Card\n15: \n16: Run this card on a built or planned interface as the last filter before delivery. Every box is binary: it passes or it fails. A single fail means the surface is not done. Fill the surface name and the section count once, then walk every box against the real render at the real breakpoints, not against an assumption.\n17: \n18: This card is the checkable form of three references. The layout boxes come from [`../references/design-process/mechanical_defaults.md`](../references/design-process/mechanical_defaults.md), the content boxes come from [`../references/design-process/copy_and_mock_data.md`](../references/design-process/copy_and_mock_data.md), and the dial calibration comes from [`../references/design-process/brief_to_dials.md`](../references/design-process/brief_to_dials.md). The Brand-vs-Product posture is set first in [`../../shared/register.md`](../../shared/register.md). Read those for the why, fill this for the check.\n19: \n20: ---\n21: \n22: ## 1. SET THE CONTEXT\n23: \n24: | Field | Value |\n25: |---|---|\n26: | Surface (page / route / file) | `__________` |\n27: | Register (from `../../shared/register.md`) | [ ] Brand (design IS the product) [ ] Product (design SERVES the product) |\n28: | Dials (from `../references/design-process/brief_to_dials.md`) | VARIANCE `___` / MOTION `___` / DENSITY `___` |\n29: | Section count (for the eyebrow math) | `___` |\n30: | Narrowest target width tested | `__________` |\n31: \n32: The posture sets how loud the surface may be. The dials set the calibration. Neither relaxes a mechanical box below: a Brand hero may still not overflow, a high-motion page may still not skip reduced motion.\n33: \n34: ---\n35: \n36: ## 2. HERO (mechanical_defaults Section 2)\n37: \n38: | Check | Pass |\n39: |---|---|\n40: | Headline is 2 lines at desktop (3 at the outside), counted at the narrowest width too | [ ] |\n41: | Container is wide and the clamp ceiling is at or under about 6rem, no hand-inserted `<br>` in the headline | [ ] |\n42: | Subtext is at or under 20 words and 3-4 lines | [ ] |\n43: | Primary CTA is visible without scroll (whole hero fits the first viewport) | [ ] |\n44: | Hero top padding is at or under about 6rem (content does not float halfway down) | [ ] |\n45: | Hero holds at or under 4 text elements (one small label, headline, subtext, CTAs), no trust strip, pricing teaser, or tagline under the CTAs | [ ] |\n46: | Hero has a real visual, not a text-plus-gradient-blob placeholder | [ ] |\n47: \n48: ---\n49: \n50: ## 3. BENTO AND GRID (mechanical_defaults Section 3)\n51: \n52: | Check | Pass |\n53: |---|---|\n54: | Cell count equals content count exactly, zero empty cells in the middle or at the end | [ ] |\n55: | The column and row interlock is verified, not assumed | [ ] |\n56: | It is a real bento (varied tile size and composition), not a uniform card grid | [ ] |\n57: | Two or more cells carry real visual variation (image, gradient, pattern, tint), not all-text same-color cells | [ ] |\n58: | The grid has rhythm, not six identical left-image right-text rows | [ ] |\n59: \n60: ---\n61: \n62: ## 4. EYEBROW AND META-LABEL SWEEP (mechanical_defaults Section 4)\n63: \n64: | Check | Pass |\n65: |---|---|\n66: | Eyebrow count is at or under `ceil(sectionCount / 3)`, hero counted as 1 | [ ] |\n67: | No two adjacent sections both carry an eyebrow | [ ] |\n68: | No numbered section markers (`01 / About`, `002 / Capabilities`) unless the section genuinely is an ordered sequence | [ ] |\n69: | No version stamps in the hero (`V0.6`, `BETA`, `INVITE-ONLY`) unless the brief is a launch | [ ] |\n70: | No generic step labels (`Stage 1`, `Phase 01`), no decoration text strip at the hero bottom | [ ] |\n71: | No scroll cues (`Scroll`, `Scroll to explore`), no locale / city / time / weather strip unless the brief is genuinely place-focused | [ ] |\n72: | Middle dot (`·`) rationed to at most one per metadata line, no decorative status dots by default | [ ] |\n73: \n74: Count `__` eyebrows against a ceiling of `__`.\n75: \n76: ---\n77: \n78: ## 5. BUTTON AND FORM CONTRAST (mechanical_defaults Section 5)\n79: \n80: | Check | Pass |\n81: |---|---|\n82: | Every button text passes contrast against its real background (4.5:1 body, 3:1 large), computed against the actual background not white | [ ] |\n83: | Ghost buttons over imagery have a backdrop, scrim, or stroke | [ ] |\n84: | No CTA label wraps to 2+ lines at desktop | [ ] |\n85: | One label per intent across the whole page (nav, hero, footer) | [ ] |\n86: | Form inputs, placeholders, focus rings, helper and error text all pass contrast against the section background | [ ] |\n87: | Label sits above the input, error text below, no placeholder-as-label | [ ] |\n88: \n89: ---\n90: \n91: ## 6. BREAKPOINT OVERFLOW AND MOBILE COLLAPSE (mechanical_defaults Sections 2, 6)\n92: \n93: | Check | Pass |\n94: |---|---|\n95: | No text overflows its container at any breakpoint (headline copy tested at every target width) | [ ] |\n96: | A max-width container holds the page, content does not stretch edge to edge on wide screens | [ ] |\n97: | Navigation renders on one line at desktop, height at or under 80px | [ ] |\n98: | Every multi-column section declares its narrow-viewport fallback explicitly | [ ] |\n99: | Viewport-height sections use a dynamic-viewport unit, never a fixed screen height | [ ] |\n100: | At most one repeat per layout family, at most two consecutive zigzag splits, no default split-header | [ ] |\n101: \n102: ---\n103: \n104: ## 7. REAL IMAGERY VS PLACEHOLDER (copy_and_mock_data Section 7)\n105: \n106: | Check | Pass |\n107: |---|---|\n108: | Real or generated imagery used first, no pure-text page with div-based fake screenshots | [ ] |\n109: | Every placeholder image seed is descriptive and unique, never the literal word `image` or a reused seed | [ ] |\n110: | Apt aspect ratio per slot, not one square reused everywhere | [ ] |\n111: | No div-based fake product UI, no sketchy hand-rolled SVG as a fallback | [ ] |\n112: | No decoration pills or photo-credit captions overlaid on placeholder images | [ ] |\n113: | Every meaningful image has real alt text | [ ] |\n114: \n115: ---\n116: \n117: ## 8. COPY AUDIT (copy_and_mock_data Sections 2, 3, 4, 5, 6)\n118: \n119: | Check | Pass |\n120: |---|---|\n121: | No lorem ipsum, no placeholder filler text, no generic or empty alt text | [ ] |\n122: | No banned filler verbs (\"Elevate\", \"Seamless\", \"Unleash\", \"Next-Gen\"), no exclamation marks in status copy, no \"Oops!\" errors | [ ] |\n123: | Copy self-audit run over every visible string, every flagged or grammatically broken string rewritten | [ ] |\n124: | No generic person names (\"Jane Doe\"), no placeholder brands (\"Acme\"), no repeated avatars or dates as filler | [ ] |\n125: | Sentence case on headers, real logos on any trust wall (not text wordmarks), logos only with no category labels | [ ] |\n126: | Every number is grounded in the brief or marked mock, no invented engineering precision, no fake-perfect round numbers | [ ] |\n127: | One copy register across the surface, matched to the register posture | [ ] |\n128: \n129: ---\n130: \n131: ## 9. MOTION MOTIVATION AND REDUCED MOTION (brief_to_dials Section 5)\n132: \n133: | Check | Pass |\n134: |---|---|\n135: | Every animation is justified in one sentence (hierarchy, storytelling, feedback, state transition), no motion-for-show | [ ] |\n136: | Motion claimed is motion shown: if MOTION is above 4 the page actually moves, if it cannot ship clean the dial dropped to a low value instead | [ ] |\n137: | At most one horizontal marquee on the page | [ ] |\n138: | Reduced motion alternative present for every animation (crossfade or instant) | [ ] |\n139: | Scroll-driven motion uses a scroll-progress or observer mechanism, not a raw scroll listener | [ ] |\n140: | Reveal animations enhance an already-visible default, content is not gated behind a class-triggered transition that can fail to fire | [ ] |\n141: \n142: ---\n143: \n144: ## 10. AI-TELL SWEEP (the cross-cutting last filter)\n145: \n146: | Check | Pass |\n147: |---|---|\n148: | Zero em-dash (U+2014) and zero en-dash-as-separator (U+2013) anywhere visible, the only dash is the regular hyphen | [ ] |\n149: | Not a templated default look spent on a free axis (cream + serif + terracotta, near-black + one acid accent, broadsheet hairlines) | [ ] |\n150: | No AI-purple or neon-glow accent by default, one accent color used identically across all sections | [ ] |\n151: | One corner-radius system applied consistently, one page theme (no section flips to inverted mode mid-page) | [ ] |\n152: | No three-equal-card feature row, no hero-metric template (big number, small label, supporting stats, gradient accent) | [ ] |\n153: | No side-stripe borders, no gradient text, no decorative glassmorphism by default | [ ] |\n154: | Icons from one allowed library, no hand-rolled SVG icon paths | [ ] |\n155: | If someone could say \"AI made that\" without doubt, it has failed: reworked until the answer is not obvious from the category alone | [ ] |\n156: \n157: ---\n158: \n159: ## 11. VERDICT\n160: \n161: | Result | Mark |\n162: |---|---|\n163: | All boxes pass | [ ] SHIP |\n164: | One or more boxes fail | [ ] FIX, list the failing box numbers below |\n165: \n166: Failing boxes: `__________`\n167: \n168: If a single box cannot be honestly checked, the surface is not done. Fix it, then re-run this card.\n\n(End of file - total 168 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"Interface Pre-Flight Card\"\ndescription: \"A mechanical fill-in pass/fail card to run on a built or planned interface before calling it done. Covers hero, bento, eyebrow and meta-label sweep, button contrast, breakpoint overflow, real imagery, copy audit, motion motivation, reduced motion, mobile collapse, and the AI-tell sweep. Every box is binary.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"interface pre-flight card\"\n  - \"ui pass fail checklist\"\n  - \"design pre-flight gate\"\n  - \"ai tell sweep card\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Interface Pre-Flight Card\n\nRun this card on a built or planned interface as the last filter before delivery. Every box is binary: it passes or it fails. A single fail means the surface is not done. Fill the surface name and the section count once, then walk every box against the real render at the real breakpoints, not against an assumption.\n\nThis card is the checkable form of three references. The layout boxes come from [`../references/design-process/mechanical_defaults.md`](../references/design-process/mechanical_defaults.md), the content boxes come from [`../references/design-process/copy_and_mock_data.md`](../references/design-process/copy_and_mock_data.md), and the dial calibration comes from [`../references/design-process/brief_to_dials.md`](../references/design-process/brief_to_dials.md). The Brand-vs-Product posture is set first in [`../../shared/register.md`](../../shared/register.md). Read those for the why, fill this for the check.\n\n---","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/assets/interface_preflight_card.md","text":"---\ntitle: \"Interface Pre-Flight Card\"\ndescription: \"A mechanical fill-in pass/fail card to run on a built or planned interface before calling it done. Covers hero, bento, eyebrow and meta-label sweep, button contrast, breakpoint overflow, real imagery, copy audit, motion motivation, reduced motion, mobile collapse, and the AI-tell sweep. Every box is binary.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"interface pre-flight card\"\n  - \"ui pass fail checklist\"\n  - \"design pre-flight gate\"\n  - \"ai tell sweep card\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.0.0.0\n---\n\n# Interface Pre-Flight Card\n\nRun this card on a built or planned interface as the last filter before delivery. Every box is binary: it passes or it fails. A single fail means the surface is not done. Fill the surface name and the section count once, then walk every box against the real render at the real breakpoints, not against an assumption.\n\nThis card is the checkable form of three references. The layout boxes come from [`../references/design-process/mechanical_defaults.md`](../references/design-process/mechanical_defaults.md), the content boxes come from [`../references/design-process/copy_and_mock_data.md`](../references/design-process/copy_and_mock_data.md), and the dial calibration comes from [`../references/design-process/brief_to_dials.md`](../references/design-process/brief_to_dials.md). The Brand-vs-Product posture is set first in [`../../shared/register.md`](../../shared/register.md). Read those for the why, fill this for the check.\n\n---\n\n## 1. SET THE CONTEXT\n\n| Field | Value |\n|---|---|\n| Surface (page / route / file) | `__________` |\n| Register (from `../../shared/register.md`) | [ ] Brand (design IS the product) [ ] Product (design SERVES the product) |\n| Dials (from `../references/design-process/brief_to_dials.md`) | VARIANCE `___` / MOTION `___` / DENSITY `___` |\n| Section count (for the eyebrow math) | `___` |\n| Narrowest target width tested | `__________` |\n\nThe posture sets how loud the surface may be. The dials set the calibration. Neither relaxes a mechanical box below: a Brand hero may still not overflow, a high-motion page may still not skip reduced motion.\n\n---\n\n## 2. HERO (mechanical_defaults Section 2)\n\n| Check | Pass |\n|---|---|\n| Headline is 2 lines at desktop (3 at the outside), counted at the narrowest width too | [ ] |\n| Container is wide and the clamp ceiling is at or under about 6rem, no hand-inserted `<br>` in the headline | [ ] |\n| Subtext is at or under 20 words and 3-4 lines | [ ] |\n| Primary CTA is visible without scroll (whole hero fits the first viewport) | [ ] |\n| Hero top padding is at or under about 6rem (content does not float halfway down) | [ ] |\n| Hero holds at or under 4 text elements (one small label, headline, subtext, CTAs), no trust strip, pricing teaser, or tagline under the CTAs | [ ] |\n| Hero has a real visual, not a text-plus-gradient-blob placeholder | [ ] |\n\n---\n\n## 3. BENTO AND GRID (mechanical_defaults Section 3)\n\n| Check | Pass |\n|---|---|\n| Cell count equals content count exactly, zero empty cells in the middle or at the end | [ ] |\n| The column and row interlock is verified, not assumed | [ ] |\n| It is a real bento (varied tile size and composition), not a uniform card grid | [ ] |\n| Two or more cells carry real visual variation (image, gradient, pattern, tint), not all-text same-color cells | [ ] |\n| The grid has rhythm, not six identical left-image right-text rows | [ ] |\n\n---\n\n## 4. EYEBROW AND META-LABEL SWEEP (mechanical_defaults Section 4)\n\n| Check | Pass |\n|---|---|\n| Eyebrow count is at or under `ceil(sectionCount / 3)`, hero counted as 1 | [ ] |\n| No two adjacent sections both carry an eyebrow | [ ] |\n| No numbered section markers (`01 / About`, `002 / Capabilities`) unless the section genuinely is an ordered sequence | [ ] |\n| No version stamps in the hero (`V0.6`, `BETA`, `INVITE-ONLY`) unless the brief is a launch | [ ] |\n| No generic step labels (`Stage 1`, `Phase 01`), no decoration text strip at the hero bottom | [ ] |\n| No scroll cues (`Scroll`, `Scroll to explore`), no locale / city / time / weather strip unless the brief is genuinely place-focused | [ ] |\n| Middle dot (`·`) rationed to at most one per metadata line, no decorative status dots by default | [ ] |\n\nCount `__` eyebrows against a ceiling of `__`.\n\n---\n\n## 5. BUTTON AND FORM CONTRAST (mechanical_defaults Section 5)\n\n| Check | Pass |\n|---|---|\n| Every button text passes contrast against its real background (4.5:1 body, 3:1 large), computed against the actual background not white | [ ] |\n| Ghost buttons over imagery have a backdrop, scrim, or stroke | [ ] |\n| No CTA label wraps to 2+ lines at desktop | [ ] |\n| One label per intent across the whole page (nav, hero, footer) | [ ] |\n| Form inputs, placeholders, focus rings, helper and error text all pass contrast against the section background | [ ] |\n| Label sits above the input, error text below, no placeholder-as-label | [ ] |\n\n---\n\n## 6. BREAKPOINT OVERFLOW AND MOBILE COLLAPSE (mechanical_defaults Sections 2, 6)\n\n| Check | Pass |\n|---|---|\n| No text overflows its container at any breakpoint (headline copy tested at every target width) | [ ] |\n| A max-width container holds the page, content does not stretch edge to edge on wide screens | [ ] |\n| Navigation renders on one line at desktop, height at or under 80px | [ ] |\n| Every multi-column section declares its narrow-viewport fallback explicitly | [ ] |\n| Viewport-height sections use a dynamic-viewport unit, never a fixed screen height | [ ] |\n| At most one repeat per layout family, at most two consecutive zigzag splits, no default split-header | [ ] |\n\n---\n\n## 7. REAL IMAGERY VS PLACEHOLDER (copy_and_mock_data Section 7)\n\n| Check | Pass |\n|---|---|\n| Real or generated imagery used first, no pure-text page with div-based fake screenshots | [ ] |\n| Every placeholder image seed is descriptive and unique, never the literal word `image` or a reused seed | [ ] |\n| Apt aspect ratio per slot, not one square reused everywhere | [ ] |\n| No div-based fake product UI, no sketchy hand-rolled SVG as a fallback | [ ] |\n| No decoration pills or photo-credit captions overlaid on placeholder images | [ ] |\n| Every meaningful image has real alt text | [ ] |\n\n---\n\n## 8. COPY AUDIT (copy_and_mock_data Sections 2, 3, 4, 5, 6)\n\n| Check | Pass |\n|---|---|\n| No lorem ipsum, no placeholder filler text, no generic or empty alt text | [ ] |\n| No banned filler verbs (\"Elevate\", \"Seamless\", \"Unleash\", \"Next-Gen\"), no exclamation marks in status copy, no \"Oops!\" errors | [ ] |\n| Copy self-audit run over every visible string, every flagged or grammatically broken string rewritten | [ ] |\n| No generic person names (\"Jane Doe\"), no placeholder brands (\"Acme\"), no repeated avatars or dates as filler | [ ] |\n| Sentence case on headers, real logos on any trust wall (not text wordmarks), logos only with no category labels | [ ] |\n| Every number is grounded in the brief or marked mock, no invented engineering precision, no fake-perfect round numbers | [ ] |\n| One copy register across the surface, matched to the register posture | [ ] |\n\n---\n\n## 9. MOTION MOTIVATION AND REDUCED MOTION (brief_to_dials Section 5)\n\n| Check | Pass |\n|---|---|\n| Every animation is justified in one sentence (hierarchy, storytelling, feedback, state transition), no motion-for-show | [ ] |\n| Motion claimed is motion shown: if MOTION is above 4 the page actually moves, if it cannot ship clean the dial dropped to a low value instead | [ ] |\n| At most one horizontal marquee on the page | [ ] |\n| Reduced motion alternative present for every animation (crossfade or instant) | [ ] |\n| Scroll-driven motion uses a scroll-progress or observer mechanism, not a raw scroll listener | [ ] |\n| Reveal animations enhance an already-visible default, content is not gated behind a class-triggered transition that can fail to fire | [ ] |\n\n---\n\n## 10. AI-TELL SWEEP (the cross-cutting last filter)\n\n| Check | Pass |\n|---|---|\n| Zero em-dash (U+2014) and zero en-dash-as-separator (U+2013) anywhere visible, the only dash is the regular hyphen | [ ] |\n| Not a templated default look spent on a free axis (cream + serif + terracotta, near-black + one acid accent, broadsheet hairlines) | [ ] |\n| No AI-purple or neon-glow accent by default, one accent color used identically across all sections | [ ] |\n| One corner-radius system applied consistently, one page theme (no section flips to inverted mode mid-page) | [ ] |\n| No three-equal-card feature row, no hero-metric template (big number, small label, supporting stats, gradient accent) | [ ] |\n| No side-stripe borders, no gradient text, no decorative glassmorphism by default | [ ] |\n| Icons from one allowed library, no hand-rolled SVG icon paths | [ ] |\n| If someone could say \"AI made that\" without doubt, it has failed: reworked until the answer is not obvious from the category alone | [ ] |\n\n---\n\n## 11. VERDICT\n\n| Result | Mark |\n|---|---|\n| All boxes pass | [ ] SHIP |\n| One or more boxes fail | [ ] FIX, list the failing box numbers below |\n\nFailing boxes: `__________`\n\nIf a single box cannot be honestly checked, the surface is not done. Fix it, then re-run this card.","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":168,"totalLines":168,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/assets/interface_preflight_card.md","time":{"start":1782532294908,"end":1782532294911}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_014eb9dfa2151398016a3f48c6a7cc81918df588fe5aa70470"}},"id":"prt_f073448df001iu3DrJV7jlbYWY","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c7affeFPHv9jEwltlvKr","messageID":"msg_f0733f1ae001lQSXfKTffNe8CR"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532294930,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c7affeFPHv9jEwltlvKr","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_wLrdXF4jRdee0j8uFVbYf43h","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md","offset":1,"limit":400},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"interface: Manual Testing Playbook\"\n3: description: \"Operator-facing reference combining the manual testing directory, integrated review and orchestration guidance, execution expectations, and per-feature validation files for the interface skill.\"\n4: version: 1.6.0.0\n5: ---\n6: \n7: # interface: Manual Testing Playbook\n8: \n9: > **EXECUTION POLICY**: Every scenario MUST be executed against the live `interface` skill and its on-disk references, scripts, and data. No mocks, no stubs, and no \"unautomatable\" verdicts. Acceptable verdicts are PASS, PARTIAL, FAIL, or SKIP with a concrete sandbox or tool-availability blocker.\n10: \n11: This document combines the full manual-validation contract for the `interface` skill into one reference. The root playbook acts as the operator directory, review protocol, and orchestration guide, while the per-feature files carry scenario-specific execution truth for distinctive, intentional interface-design behavior.\n12: \n13: ---\n14: \n15: This playbook package adopts the split-document pattern for the `design-interface` skill. The root document acts as the directory, review surface, and orchestration guide, while per-feature execution detail lives in the numbered category folders at the playbook root.\n16: \n17: Canonical package artifacts:\n18: - `manual_testing_playbook.md`\n19: - `01--direction-freedom-and-deviation/`\n20: - `02--brief-pinning-and-precedence/`\n21: - `03--quality-floor-gate/`\n22: - `04--system-as-critique-against/`\n23: - `05--abstention-and-routing/`\n24: - `06--licensing-and-provenance/`\n25: - `07--real-ui-loop/`\n26: - `08--design-references-routing/`\n27: - `09--mechanical-preflight-card/`\n28: - `10--mechanical-layout-gate/`\n29: - `11--content-and-mock-data-gate/`\n30: - `12--brief-to-dials-intake/`\n31: \n32: ---\n33: \n34: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n35: \n36: This playbook provides 14 deterministic scenarios across 12 categories validating the `interface` skill surface. Each scenario maps to a dedicated per-feature file with exact prompt, command sequence, expected signals, evidence, pass/fail criteria, and failure triage.\n37: \n38: Coverage note (2026-06-26): the playbook covers the free-axis brainstorm-critique-deviate process against the three named AI-default clusters, brief-pinning precedence where the brief always wins, the objective quality-floor gate sourced from `ux_quality_reference.md`, the system-as-critique-against use where a real design system is read live as the default to deviate from with a negative control that it is never surfaced as a chooser and never copied, abstention and routing to `sk-code` for pure-logic work and to `sk-doc` for documentation work, licensing and provenance integrity confirming the skill is Apache-2.0 only with no vendored MIT material remaining, the real-UI loop covering reuse-before-generate when a design system is present and the render fidelity check gated on the quality floor and the anti-default critique each with a negative control, and the design-references hybrid initiative/ask routing where the skill pulls one real-world Mobbin or Refero reference on its own initiative when a convention-heavy category benefits and a subscription is connected, asks the user when borderline or unknown, and falls back to the generic process otherwise, with a negative control that it is never a chooser and never copied. It also covers the mechanical pre-flight card walked box by box as the binary last filter before delivery, the mechanical layout gate where the hero lines, bento cells, and eyebrows are counted and button contrast is computed against the real background, the copy and mock-data content gate swept over the real strings for lorem, AI-tell phrasing, fake precision, one copy register, and image-seed discipline, and the brief-to-dials Design Read intake that reads a brief into the variance, motion, and density dials after the register posture is set with a negative control that the dials are never surfaced as a chooser. Per-feature files anchor directly to `SKILL.md`, the `references/` docs, and `assets/interface_preflight_card.md`.\n39: \n40: ### Realistic Test Model\n41: \n42: 1. A realistic design request is given to an orchestrator.\n43: 2. The orchestrator decides whether to plan the look locally, hand implementation to `sk-code`, or route away from a non-visual task.\n44: 3. The operator captures the exact prompt, command transcript, the design plan or routing decision, and the user-visible outcome.\n45: 4. The scenario passes only when the workflow is sound and the returned plan, gate result, or routing decision would satisfy a real user.\n46: \n47: ### What Each Feature File Should Explain\n48: \n49: - The realistic user request that should trigger the behavior\n50: - The operator or orchestrator-facing prompt using the canonical scenario voice\n51: - The expected execution process, including routing to `sk-code` or `sk-doc` when relevant\n52: - The desired user-visible outcome\n53: - The source anchors that justify pass/fail criteria\n54: \n55: ---\n56: \n57: ## 2. GLOBAL PRECONDITIONS\n58: \n59: 1. Working directory is the repository root.\n60: 2. `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md` and all files under `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/references/` resolve on disk.\n61: 3. `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/LICENSE.txt` resolves on disk and is the skill's single Apache-2.0 license.\n62: 4. The operator can run `python3`, `rg`, and `git diff` from the repository root.\n63: 5. Routing scenarios assume `sk-code` and `sk-doc` are installed under `.opencode/skills/`; the design-system grounding scenario assumes a real design system you own is available to read live, the render fidelity scenario assumes `mcp-chrome-devtools`, and the design-references routing scenario assumes the Mobbin or Refero MCPs resolve through Code Mode with a connected subscription for its initiative path (its fall-back path stays exercisable without one), otherwise record SKIP with the missing dependency.\n64: 6. The mechanical pre-flight card, the mechanical layout gate, and the content gate each assume the operator supplies a real built or planned UI as the fixture so the boxes, counts, and sweeps run against a concrete render. The brief-to-dials intake assumes a concrete brief is supplied so the dials read from real signals.\n65: 7. No scenario writes design-system files, copies any external design-system content into the skill, or edits the skill's reference files. Any such mutation is contradictory evidence.\n66: \n67: ---\n68: \n69: ## 3. GLOBAL EVIDENCE REQUIREMENTS\n70: \n71: - Exact user request used\n72: - Exact operator or orchestrator prompt used\n73: - Command transcript, including exit status where a command is executed\n74: - Design plan, gate result, or routing decision produced\n75: - The expected-default pattern named when a scenario critiques against the data\n76: - Source-reference mapping to `SKILL.md`, `references/design-process/design_principles.md`, `references/design-process/ux_quality_reference.md`, or `references/design-grounding/design_inventory.md`\n77: - Routing notes when the workflow hands off to `sk-code` or `sk-doc`\n78: - Final scenario verdict with rationale: PASS, PARTIAL, FAIL, or SKIP\n79: \n80: ---\n81: \n82: ## 4. DETERMINISTIC COMMAND NOTATION\n83: \n84: - Bash commands shown as `bash: <command>`.\n85: - Skill-routing decisions shown as `route: -> <skill-name>`.\n86: - Agent prompts shown as `agent: <instruction>`.\n87: - `->` separates sequential steps inside one deterministic command sequence.\n88: - All reads of a real design system are live and read-only. Any generated design-system file, copied external design-system content, or edited reference is contradictory evidence.\n89: \n90: ---\n91: \n92: ## 5. REVIEW PROTOCOL AND RELEASE READINESS\n93: \n94: ### Inputs Required\n95: \n96: 1. `manual_testing_playbook.md`\n97: 2. Referenced per-feature files under `manual_testing_playbook/NN--category-name/`\n98: 3. Scenario execution evidence from section 3\n99: 4. Feature-to-scenario coverage map from section 20\n100: 5. Triage notes for every PARTIAL, FAIL, or SKIP verdict\n101: \n102: ### Scenario Acceptance Rules\n103: \n104: For each executed scenario, check:\n105: \n106: 1. Preconditions were satisfied.\n107: 2. Prompt and command sequence were executed as written.\n108: 3. Expected signals are present without contradictory evidence.\n109: 4. Evidence is complete and readable.\n110: 5. Pass/fail criteria cite the relevant `interface` source file.\n111: 6. Outcome rationale is explicit and useful to a real user.\n112: \n113: Scenario verdict:\n114: - `PASS`: all acceptance checks true\n115: - `PARTIAL`: core behavior works but non-critical evidence or metadata is incomplete\n116: - `FAIL`: expected behavior missing, contradictory output, brief override, generator or persistence use, or critical evidence missing\n117: - `SKIP`: execution blocked by a named sandbox, missing skill, or unavailable fixture\n118: \n119: ### Feature Verdict Rules\n120: \n121: - `PASS`: the mapped scenario is PASS.\n122: - `PARTIAL`: the mapped scenario is PARTIAL and no critical check failed.\n123: - `FAIL`: the mapped scenario is FAIL.\n124: \n125: Hard rule:\n126: - Any critical-path scenario FAIL (ID-001, ID-002, ID-003, ID-004) blocks release readiness.\n127: \n128: ### Release Readiness Rule\n129: \n130: Release is READY only when:\n131: \n132: 1. No feature verdict is FAIL.\n133: 2. All critical-path scenarios are PASS or explicitly SKIP for environment-only reasons.\n134: 3. Coverage is 100% of playbook scenarios defined by the root index and backed by per-feature files (`COVERED_FEATURES == TOTAL_FEATURES == 14`).\n135: 4. No unresolved blocking triage item remains.\n136: 5. No scenario exposed a generator or persistence surface and no scenario overrode a pinned brief.\n137: \n138: ### Root-vs-Feature Rule\n139: \n140: Keep global verdict logic in this root playbook. Put scenario-specific caveats, fixture assumptions, and source anchors in the matching per-feature files.\n141: \n142: ### Release Review Checklist\n143: \n144: Before declaring this playbook release-ready, confirm:\n145: \n146: 1. Root validator is clean.\n147: 2. Per-feature structural sweep checks all 14 files.\n148: 3. No forbidden sidecars exist.\n149: 4. Every table row has exactly 9 columns.\n150: 5. Every scenario prompt is realistic per the RCAF-vs-natural-human heuristic in sk-doc creation reference section 5.\n151: 6. Every SCENARIO CONTRACT prompt equals its table prompt.\n152: 7. Every pass/fail rule cites a real interface source file.\n153: 8. The system-as-critique-against scenario records both the named default look and the no-chooser, no-cache negative control.\n154: 9. The licensing scenario records the actual provenance state honestly, confirming the skill is Apache-2.0 only with no vendored MIT material remaining.\n155: 10. The real-UI loop scenarios record their negative controls: no style-preset menu for reuse-before-generate, and no finished-design claim from a build that never rendered or a file write with no visible UI for the fidelity check.\n156: 11. The design-references routing scenario records its three branches (initiative, ask, fall-back), the Mobbin-vs-Refero source pick, and its negative control: no chooser or gallery, no copied or cached reference, read live, and grounding kept upstream.\n157: 12. The mechanical pre-flight card scenario records the filled context table, a binary mark on every box, the failing box numbers, and a SHIP verdict reached only with zero failing boxes.\n158: 13. The mechanical layout gate scenario records the counted hero lines, bento cells, and eyebrows against the `ceil(sectionCount / 3)` ceiling, with button contrast computed against the real background rather than assumed white.\n159: 14. The content gate scenario records the sweeps run over the real strings, every number listed with its grounding, and the single copy register named and matched to the posture.\n160: 15. The brief-to-dials intake scenario records the register posture set first, the one-line Design Read with the three dial values, and its negative control: the dials kept internal and never surfaced as a chooser.\n161: 16. The final report separates playbook defects from interface product defects.\n162: \n163: ---\n164: \n165: ## 6. SUB-AGENT ORCHESTRATION AND WAVE PLANNING\n166: \n167: ### Purpose\n168: \n169: This section records wave planning and capacity guidance for executing the 14-scenario design battery. It is not a runtime support matrix by itself.\n170: \n171: ### Operational Rules\n172: \n173: 1. Probe runtime capacity at start: script availability, data-set presence, and the presence of `sk-code` and `sk-doc`.\n174: 2. Reserve one coordinator to maintain the verdict table and prompt-equality audit.\n175: 3. Saturate remaining worker slots only when scenarios use disjoint read-only scopes.\n176: 4. Pre-assign explicit scenario IDs and matching per-feature files to each wave before execution.\n177: 5. Run the routing scenarios in a dedicated wave so the abstention decision can be compared against the same brief framing.\n178: 6. After each wave, save evidence paths and verdict rationale before starting the next wave.\n179: 7. Record utilization table, per-feature file references, and evidence paths in the final report.\n180: \n181: ### Suggested Waves\n182: \n183: | Wave | Categories | Scenarios | Rationale |\n184: |---|---|---|---|\n185: | 1 | Direction freedom + brief pinning | ID-001, ID-002 | The deviate-vs-obey precedence pair is the core behavior and isolates cleanly |\n186: | 2 | Quality floor + system critique | ID-003, ID-004 | The objective gate reads on-disk references while the critique-against scenario reads one real design system live, and both are read-only and isolate cleanly |\n187: | 3 | Abstention and routing | ID-005, ID-006 | Routing away from non-visual work is read-only and isolates from the design path |\n188: | 4 | Real-UI loop | ID-008, ID-009 | Reuse-before-generate and the fidelity check share the real-UI loop protocol and the render surface |\n189: | 5 | Design-references routing | ID-010 | The initiative/ask/fall-back gate reads one design-references doc and exercises a paid-lookup decision, so it runs in its own wave to isolate the subscription-status branch |\n190: | 6 | Mechanical pre-flight + layout + content gates | ID-011, ID-012, ID-013 | The three delivery gates all read on-disk references against one supplied built UI fixture, so they share the render fixture and isolate cleanly |\n191: | 7 | Brief-to-dials intake | ID-014 | The Design Read intake reads a brief into the dials after the register posture, so it runs with the other intake-shaped checks and isolates the dial calibration |\n192: | 8 | Licensing and provenance | ID-007 | Provenance integrity is a static-inspection check and runs last |\n193: \n194: ### What Belongs In Per-Feature Files\n195: \n196: - Real user request\n197: - Prompt field with the canonical text for this scenario\n198: - Expected design plan, gate result, or routing decision\n199: - Expected handoff to `sk-code` or `sk-doc` when relevant\n200: - Desired user-visible outcome\n201: - Feature-specific acceptance caveats and source anchors\n202: \n203: ---\n204: \n205: ## 7. DIRECTION FREEDOM AND DEVIATION (ID-001)\n206: \n207: This category covers 1 scenario while the linked feature file remains the canonical execution contract.\n208: \n209: ### ID-001 | Free-axis brainstorm critique and deliberate deviation\n210: \n211: #### Description\n212: \n213: A design task with free axes that must brainstorm a token system, critique it against the three AI-default clusters, and deviate deliberately rather than ship a templated default.\n214: \n215: #### Scenario Contract\n216: \n217: Prompt: `Design a landing page for an artisan letterpress studio; the brand has no fixed colors or fonts yet, so make it feel distinctive rather than generic.`\n218: \n219: Desired user-visible outcome: A grounded design plan with a named token system whose free axes deviate deliberately from the three AI-default looks, each deviation justified against the brief.\n220: \n221: #### Test Execution\n222: \n223: > **Feature File:** [ID-001](01--direction-freedom-and-deviation/001-free-axis-brainstorm-and-deviation.md)\n224: \n225: ---\n226: \n227: ## 8. BRIEF PINNING AND PRECEDENCE (ID-002)\n228: \n229: This category covers 1 scenario while the linked feature file remains the canonical execution contract.\n230: \n231: ### ID-002 | Pinned brief is followed verbatim\n232: \n233: #### Description\n234: \n235: A brief that pins the visual direction, including an AI-default look, must be followed verbatim and never overridden by the skill's deviation guidance.\n236: \n237: #### Scenario Contract\n238: \n239: Prompt: `Build the hero using exactly this direction: cream #F4F1EA background, a high-contrast serif display, and a terracotta accent. Do not change the palette.`\n240: \n241: Desired user-visible outcome: A design plan that follows the pinned cream-serif-terracotta direction verbatim, with no substitution and no deviation argument applied to the pinned axes.\n242: \n243: #### Test Execution\n244: \n245: > **Feature File:** [ID-002](02--brief-pinning-and-precedence/002-pinned-brief-followed-verbatim.md)\n246: \n247: ---\n248: \n249: ## 9. QUALITY FLOOR GATE (ID-003)\n250: \n251: This category covers 1 scenario while the linked feature file remains the canonical execution contract.\n252: \n253: ### ID-003 | Quality-floor gate on a built UI\n254: \n255: #### Description\n256: \n257: A built UI is checked against the objective quality floor in `ux_quality_reference.md` across contrast, focus, reduced motion, touch targets, and responsive behavior.\n258: \n259: #### Scenario Contract\n260: \n261: Prompt: `Check this finished landing page against the accessibility and quality floor and tell me what fails before I ship.`\n262: \n263: Desired user-visible outcome: A pass/fail gate report keyed to the `ux_quality_reference.md` rules, naming each failing rule with the specific floor it breaks and how to fix it.\n264: \n265: #### Test Execution\n266: \n267: > **Feature File:** [ID-003](03--quality-floor-gate/003-quality-floor-gate-on-built-ui.md)\n268: \n269: ---\n270: \n271: ## 10. SYSTEM AS CRITIQUE-AGAINST (ID-004)\n272: \n273: This category covers 1 scenario while the linked feature file remains the canonical execution contract.\n274: \n275: ### ID-004 | Read a design system as the default, then deviate\n276: \n277: #### Description\n278: \n279: Reading a matching real design system live returns one realized look for a subject, which is then deviated from rather than copied, with a negative control proving it is never surfaced as a chooser menu and never cached into the skill.\n280: \n281: #### Scenario Contract\n282: \n283: Prompt: `Look up the typical look for a luxury e-commerce site so we know the cliche, then propose something that deliberately moves off it.`\n284: \n285: Desired user-visible outcome: A named expected-default look from a real system, a justified deviation away from it, and confirmation that the system is read live, resolved as one system rather than a chooser, and never copied into the skill.\n286: \n287: #### Test Execution\n288: \n289: > **Feature File:** [ID-004](04--system-as-critique-against/004-query-default-then-deviate.md)\n290: \n291: ---\n292: \n293: ## 11. ABSTENTION AND ROUTING (ID-005..ID-006)\n294: \n295: This category covers 2 scenarios while the linked feature files remain the canonical execution contract.\n296: \n297: ### ID-005 | Pure-logic task routes away to sk-code\n298: \n299: #### Description\n300: \n301: A pure-logic or back-end task with no visual surface routes away from the design skill to `sk-code` instead of producing a design plan.\n302: \n303: #### Scenario Contract\n304: \n305: Prompt: `Write a function that dedupes and sorts a list of order records by timestamp, then total the amounts per customer.`\n306: \n307: Desired user-visible outcome: A clear routing decision that this is non-visual work for `sk-code`, with no palette, typography, or layout plan produced.\n308: \n309: #### Test Execution\n310: \n311: > **Feature File:** [ID-005](05--abstention-and-routing/005-pure-logic-routes-to-sk-code.md)\n312: \n313: ### ID-006 | Documentation task routes away to sk-doc\n314: \n315: #### Description\n316: \n317: A documentation or prose task with no interface surface routes away from the design skill to `sk-doc` instead of producing a design plan.\n318: \n319: #### Scenario Contract\n320: \n321: Prompt: `Write the README for this CLI tool: install steps, usage examples, and a troubleshooting section.`\n322: \n323: Desired user-visible outcome: A clear routing decision that this is documentation work for `sk-doc`, with no design token system produced.\n324: \n325: #### Test Execution\n326: \n327: > **Feature File:** [ID-006](05--abstention-and-routing/006-docs-task-routes-to-sk-doc.md)\n328: \n329: ---\n330: \n331: ## 12. LICENSING AND PROVENANCE (ID-007)\n332: \n333: This category covers 1 scenario while the linked feature file remains the canonical execution contract.\n334: \n335: ### ID-007 | Licensing and provenance integrity\n336: \n337: #### Description\n338: \n339: Provenance is intact: the vendored Apache-2.0 principles are unchanged from upstream, `LICENSE.txt` resolves on disk, and a de-vendor grep confirms no vendored MIT data, search-script, vendored-license, or third party notice material remains, so the skill is Apache-2.0 only.\n340: \n341: #### Scenario Contract\n342: \n343: Prompt: `Confirm the design data and principles in this skill are properly licensed and attributed before we ship it.`\n344: \n345: Desired user-visible outcome: A provenance report confirming `design_principles.md` is unchanged Apache-2.0 content, `LICENSE.txt` is present, and the skill is Apache-2.0 only with no vendored MIT material or notices remaining.\n346: \n347: #### Test Execution\n348: \n349: > **Feature File:** [ID-007](06--licensing-and-provenance/007-licensing-and-provenance-integrity.md)\n350: \n351: ---\n352: \n353: ## 13. REAL-UI LOOP (ID-008..ID-009)\n354: \n355: This category covers 2 scenarios while the linked feature files remain the canonical execution contract.\n356: \n357: ### ID-008 | Reuse before generate when a design system is present\n358: \n359: #### Description\n360: \n361: When a design system is present, the real-UI loop searches the system's registered components and tokens before authoring net-new, with a negative control proving no style-preset or pick-a-vibe menu exists.\n362: \n363: #### Scenario Contract\n364: \n365: Prompt: `Build this pricing section using our existing design system; reuse the components and tokens we already have before making anything new.`\n366: \n367: Desired user-visible outcome: A result that reuses the system's components and tokens where they fit, justifies any net-new authoring against the gap, and offers no choosable style axis.\n368: \n369: #### Test Execution\n370: \n371: > **Feature File:** [ID-008](07--real-ui-loop/008-reuse-before-generate-with-design-system.md)\n372: \n373: ### ID-009 | Render fidelity check gated on the quality floor and anti-default critique\n374: \n375: #### Description\n376: \n377: The fidelity check inspects the dev-server build's render via an `mcp-chrome-devtools` screenshot and judges it against the quality floor and the anti-default critique, with a negative control proving a design is not claimed from a build that never rendered or a file write with no visible UI.\n378: \n379: #### Scenario Contract\n380: \n381: Prompt: `Verify the built UI actually rendered a design that matches the intent, and tell me if it clears our quality bar.`\n382: \n383: Desired user-visible outcome: A fidelity verdict over the real render that names the quality-floor result and the anti-default result, with no pixel-diff claim and no design claimed from a build that never rendered.\n384: \n385: #### Test Execution\n386: \n387: > **Feature File:** [ID-009](07--real-ui-loop/009-render-fidelity-check.md)\n388: \n389: ---\n390: \n391: ## 14. DESIGN-REFERENCES ROUTING (ID-010)\n392: \n393: This category covers 1 scenario while the linked feature file remains the canonical execution contract.\n394: \n395: ### ID-010 | Design-references initiative/ask routing for Mobbin and Refero\n396: \n397: #### Description\n398: \n399: The hybrid initiative/ask routing pulls ONE real-world Mobbin or Refero reference on its own initiative when a convention-heavy category benefits and a subscription is connected, asks the user when borderline or the subscription is unknown, and falls back to the generic anti-default process otherwise, picking Mobbin for app/iOS and Refero for web/styles, with a negative control proving it is never a chooser and never copied.\n400: \n\n(Showing lines 1-400 of 537. Use offset=401 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"interface: Manual Testing Playbook\"\ndescription: \"Operator-facing reference combining the manual testing directory, integrated review and orchestration guidance, execution expectations, and per-feature validation files for the interface skill.\"\nversion: 1.6.0.0\n---\n\n# interface: Manual Testing Playbook\n\n> **EXECUTION POLICY**: Every scenario MUST be executed against the live `interface` skill and its on-disk references, scripts, and data. No mocks, no stubs, and no \"unautomatable\" verdicts. Acceptable verdicts are PASS, PARTIAL, FAIL, or SKIP with a concrete sandbox or tool-availability blocker.\n\nThis document combines the full manual-validation contract for the `interface` skill into one reference. The root playbook acts as the operator directory, review protocol, and orchestration guide, while the per-feature files carry scenario-specific execution truth for distinctive, intentional interface-design behavior.\n\n---\n\nThis playbook package adopts the split-document pattern for the `design-interface` skill. The root document acts as the directory, review surface, and orchestration guide, while per-feature execution detail lives in the numbered category folders at the playbook root.\n\nCanonical package artifacts:\n- `manual_testing_playbook.md`\n- `01--direction-freedom-and-deviation/`\n- `02--brief-pinning-and-precedence/`","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md","text":"---\ntitle: \"interface: Manual Testing Playbook\"\ndescription: \"Operator-facing reference combining the manual testing directory, integrated review and orchestration guidance, execution expectations, and per-feature validation files for the interface skill.\"\nversion: 1.6.0.0\n---\n\n# interface: Manual Testing Playbook\n\n> **EXECUTION POLICY**: Every scenario MUST be executed against the live `interface` skill and its on-disk references, scripts, and data. No mocks, no stubs, and no \"unautomatable\" verdicts. Acceptable verdicts are PASS, PARTIAL, FAIL, or SKIP with a concrete sandbox or tool-availability blocker.\n\nThis document combines the full manual-validation contract for the `interface` skill into one reference. The root playbook acts as the operator directory, review protocol, and orchestration guide, while the per-feature files carry scenario-specific execution truth for distinctive, intentional interface-design behavior.\n\n---\n\nThis playbook package adopts the split-document pattern for the `design-interface` skill. The root document acts as the directory, review surface, and orchestration guide, while per-feature execution detail lives in the numbered category folders at the playbook root.\n\nCanonical package artifacts:\n- `manual_testing_playbook.md`\n- `01--direction-freedom-and-deviation/`\n- `02--brief-pinning-and-precedence/`\n- `03--quality-floor-gate/`\n- `04--system-as-critique-against/`\n- `05--abstention-and-routing/`\n- `06--licensing-and-provenance/`\n- `07--real-ui-loop/`\n- `08--design-references-routing/`\n- `09--mechanical-preflight-card/`\n- `10--mechanical-layout-gate/`\n- `11--content-and-mock-data-gate/`\n- `12--brief-to-dials-intake/`\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\nThis playbook provides 14 deterministic scenarios across 12 categories validating the `interface` skill surface. Each scenario maps to a dedicated per-feature file with exact prompt, command sequence, expected signals, evidence, pass/fail criteria, and failure triage.\n\nCoverage note (2026-06-26): the playbook covers the free-axis brainstorm-critique-deviate process against the three named AI-default clusters, brief-pinning precedence where the brief always wins, the objective quality-floor gate sourced from `ux_quality_reference.md`, the system-as-critique-against use where a real design system is read live as the default to deviate from with a negative control that it is never surfaced as a chooser and never copied, abstention and routing to `sk-code` for pure-logic work and to `sk-doc` for documentation work, licensing and provenance integrity confirming the skill is Apache-2.0 only with no vendored MIT material remaining, the real-UI loop covering reuse-before-generate when a design system is present and the render fidelity check gated on the quality floor and the anti-default critique each with a negative control, and the design-references hybrid initiative/ask routing where the skill pulls one real-world Mobbin or Refero reference on its own initiative when a convention-heavy category benefits and a subscription is connected, asks the user when borderline or unknown, and falls back to the generic process otherwise, with a negative control that it is never a chooser and never copied. It also covers the mechanical pre-flight card walked box by box as the binary last filter before delivery, the mechanical layout gate where the hero lines, bento cells, and eyebrows are counted and button contrast is computed against the real background, the copy and mock-data content gate swept over the real strings for lorem, AI-tell phrasing, fake precision, one copy register, and image-seed discipline, and the brief-to-dials Design Read intake that reads a brief into the variance, motion, and density dials after the register posture is set with a negative control that the dials are never surfaced as a chooser. Per-feature files anchor directly to `SKILL.md`, the `references/` docs, and `assets/interface_preflight_card.md`.\n\n### Realistic Test Model\n\n1. A realistic design request is given to an orchestrator.\n2. The orchestrator decides whether to plan the look locally, hand implementation to `sk-code`, or route away from a non-visual task.\n3. The operator captures the exact prompt, command transcript, the design plan or routing decision, and the user-visible outcome.\n4. The scenario passes only when the workflow is sound and the returned plan, gate result, or routing decision would satisfy a real user.\n\n### What Each Feature File Should Explain\n\n- The realistic user request that should trigger the behavior\n- The operator or orchestrator-facing prompt using the canonical scenario voice\n- The expected execution process, including routing to `sk-code` or `sk-doc` when relevant\n- The desired user-visible outcome\n- The source anchors that justify pass/fail criteria\n\n---\n\n## 2. GLOBAL PRECONDITIONS\n\n1. Working directory is the repository root.\n2. `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md` and all files under `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/references/` resolve on disk.\n3. `.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/LICENSE.txt` resolves on disk and is the skill's single Apache-2.0 license.\n4. The operator can run `python3`, `rg`, and `git diff` from the repository root.\n5. Routing scenarios assume `sk-code` and `sk-doc` are installed under `.opencode/skills/`; the design-system grounding scenario assumes a real design system you own is available to read live, the render fidelity scenario assumes `mcp-chrome-devtools`, and the design-references routing scenario assumes the Mobbin or Refero MCPs resolve through Code Mode with a connected subscription for its initiative path (its fall-back path stays exercisable without one), otherwise record SKIP with the missing dependency.\n6. The mechanical pre-flight card, the mechanical layout gate, and the content gate each assume the operator supplies a real built or planned UI as the fixture so the boxes, counts, and sweeps run against a concrete render. The brief-to-dials intake assumes a concrete brief is supplied so the dials read from real signals.\n7. No scenario writes design-system files, copies any external design-system content into the skill, or edits the skill's reference files. Any such mutation is contradictory evidence.\n\n---\n\n## 3. GLOBAL EVIDENCE REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Exact user request used\n- Exact operator or orchestrator prompt used\n- Command transcript, including exit status where a command is executed\n- Design plan, gate result, or routing decision produced\n- The expected-default pattern named when a scenario critiques against the data\n- Source-reference mapping to `SKILL.md`, `references/design-process/design_principles.md`, `references/design-process/ux_quality_reference.md`, or `references/design-grounding/design_inventory.md`\n- Routing notes when the workflow hands off to `sk-code` or `sk-doc`\n- Final scenario verdict with rationale: PASS, PARTIAL, FAIL, or SKIP\n\n---\n\n## 4. DETERMINISTIC COMMAND NOTATION\n\n- Bash commands shown as `bash: <command>`.\n- Skill-routing decisions shown as `route: -> <skill-name>`.\n- Agent prompts shown as `agent: <instruction>`.\n- `->` separates sequential steps inside one deterministic command sequence.\n- All reads of a real design system are live and read-only. Any generated design-system file, copied external design-system content, or edited reference is contradictory evidence.\n\n---\n\n## 5. REVIEW PROTOCOL AND RELEASE READINESS\n\n### Inputs Required\n\n1. `manual_testing_playbook.md`\n2. Referenced per-feature files under `manual_testing_playbook/NN--category-name/`\n3. Scenario execution evidence from section 3\n4. Feature-to-scenario coverage map from section 20\n5. Triage notes for every PARTIAL, FAIL, or SKIP verdict\n\n### Scenario Acceptance Rules\n\nFor each executed scenario, check:\n\n1. Preconditions were satisfied.\n2. Prompt and command sequence were executed as written.\n3. Expected signals are present without contradictory evidence.\n4. Evidence is complete and readable.\n5. Pass/fail criteria cite the relevant `interface` source file.\n6. Outcome rationale is explicit and useful to a real user.\n\nScenario verdict:\n- `PASS`: all acceptance checks true\n- `PARTIAL`: core behavior works but non-critical evidence or metadata is incomplete\n- `FAIL`: expected behavior missing, contradictory output, brief override, generator or persistence use, or critical evidence missing\n- `SKIP`: execution blocked by a named sandbox, missing skill, or unavailable fixture\n\n### Feature Verdict Rules\n\n- `PASS`: the mapped scenario is PASS.\n- `PARTIAL`: the mapped scenario is PARTIAL and no critical check failed.\n- `FAIL`: the mapped scenario is FAIL.\n\nHard rule:\n- Any critical-path scenario FAIL (ID-001, ID-002, ID-003, ID-004) blocks release readiness.\n\n### Release Readiness Rule\n\nRelease is READY only when:\n\n1. No feature verdict is FAIL.\n2. All critical-path scenarios are PASS or explicitly SKIP for environment-only reasons.\n3. Coverage is 100% of playbook scenarios defined by the root index and backed by per-feature files (`COVERED_FEATURES == TOTAL_FEATURES == 14`).\n4. No unresolved blocking triage item remains.\n5. No scenario exposed a generator or persistence surface and no scenario overrode a pinned brief.\n\n### Root-vs-Feature Rule\n\nKeep global verdict logic in this root playbook. Put scenario-specific caveats, fixture assumptions, and source anchors in the matching per-feature files.\n\n### Release Review Checklist\n\nBefore declaring this playbook release-ready, confirm:\n\n1. Root validator is clean.\n2. Per-feature structural sweep checks all 14 files.\n3. No forbidden sidecars exist.\n4. Every table row has exactly 9 columns.\n5. Every scenario prompt is realistic per the RCAF-vs-natural-human heuristic in sk-doc creation reference section 5.\n6. Every SCENARIO CONTRACT prompt equals its table prompt.\n7. Every pass/fail rule cites a real interface source file.\n8. The system-as-critique-against scenario records both the named default look and the no-chooser, no-cache negative control.\n9. The licensing scenario records the actual provenance state honestly, confirming the skill is Apache-2.0 only with no vendored MIT material remaining.\n10. The real-UI loop scenarios record their negative controls: no style-preset menu for reuse-before-generate, and no finished-design claim from a build that never rendered or a file write with no visible UI for the fidelity check.\n11. The design-references routing scenario records its three branches (initiative, ask, fall-back), the Mobbin-vs-Refero source pick, and its negative control: no chooser or gallery, no copied or cached reference, read live, and grounding kept upstream.\n12. The mechanical pre-flight card scenario records the filled context table, a binary mark on every box, the failing box numbers, and a SHIP verdict reached only with zero failing boxes.\n13. The mechanical layout gate scenario records the counted hero lines, bento cells, and eyebrows against the `ceil(sectionCount / 3)` ceiling, with button contrast computed against the real background rather than assumed white.\n14. The content gate scenario records the sweeps run over the real strings, every number listed with its grounding, and the single copy register named and matched to the posture.\n15. The brief-to-dials intake scenario records the register posture set first, the one-line Design Read with the three dial values, and its negative control: the dials kept internal and never surfaced as a chooser.\n16. The final report separates playbook defects from interface product defects.\n\n---\n\n## 6. SUB-AGENT ORCHESTRATION AND WAVE PLANNING\n\n### Purpose\n\nThis section records wave planning and capacity guidance for executing the 14-scenario design battery. It is not a runtime support matrix by itself.\n\n### Operational Rules\n\n1. Probe runtime capacity at start: script availability, data-set presence, and the presence of `sk-code` and `sk-doc`.\n2. Reserve one coordinator to maintain the verdict table and prompt-equality audit.\n3. Saturate remaining worker slots only when scenarios use disjoint read-only scopes.\n4. Pre-assign explicit scenario IDs and matching per-feature files to each wave before execution.\n5. Run the routing scenarios in a dedicated wave so the abstention decision can be compared against the same brief framing.\n6. After each wave, save evidence paths and verdict rationale before starting the next wave.\n7. Record utilization table, per-feature file references, and evidence paths in the final report.\n\n### Suggested Waves\n\n| Wave | Categories | Scenarios | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | Direction freedom + brief pinning | ID-001, ID-002 | The deviate-vs-obey precedence pair is the core behavior and isolates cleanly |\n| 2 | Quality floor + system critique | ID-003, ID-004 | The objective gate reads on-disk references while the critique-against scenario reads one real design system live, and both are read-only and isolate cleanly |\n| 3 | Abstention and routing | ID-005, ID-006 | Routing away from non-visual work is read-only and isolates from the design path |\n| 4 | Real-UI loop | ID-008, ID-009 | Reuse-before-generate and the fidelity check share the real-UI loop protocol and the render surface |\n| 5 | Design-references routing | ID-010 | The initiative/ask/fall-back gate reads one design-references doc and exercises a paid-lookup decision, so it runs in its own wave to isolate the subscription-status branch |\n| 6 | Mechanical pre-flight + layout + content gates | ID-011, ID-012, ID-013 | The three delivery gates all read on-disk references against one supplied built UI fixture, so they share the render fixture and isolate cleanly |\n| 7 | Brief-to-dials intake | ID-014 | The Design Read intake reads a brief into the dials after the register posture, so it runs with the other intake-shaped checks and isolates the dial calibration |\n| 8 | Licensing and provenance | ID-007 | Provenance integrity is a static-inspection check and runs last |\n\n### What Belongs In Per-Feature Files\n\n- Real user request\n- Prompt field with the canonical text for this scenario\n- Expected design plan, gate result, or routing decision\n- Expected handoff to `sk-code` or `sk-doc` when relevant\n- Desired user-visible outcome\n- Feature-specific acceptance caveats and source anchors\n\n---\n\n## 7. DIRECTION FREEDOM AND DEVIATION (ID-001)\n\nThis category covers 1 scenario while the linked feature file remains the canonical execution contract.\n\n### ID-001 | Free-axis brainstorm critique and deliberate deviation\n\n#### Description\n\nA design task with free axes that must brainstorm a token system, critique it against the three AI-default clusters, and deviate deliberately rather than ship a templated default.\n\n#### Scenario Contract\n\nPrompt: `Design a landing page for an artisan letterpress studio; the brand has no fixed colors or fonts yet, so make it feel distinctive rather than generic.`\n\nDesired user-visible outcome: A grounded design plan with a named token system whose free axes deviate deliberately from the three AI-default looks, each deviation justified against the brief.\n\n#### Test Execution\n\n> **Feature File:** [ID-001](01--direction-freedom-and-deviation/001-free-axis-brainstorm-and-deviation.md)\n\n---\n\n## 8. BRIEF PINNING AND PRECEDENCE (ID-002)\n\nThis category covers 1 scenario while the linked feature file remains the canonical execution contract.\n\n### ID-002 | Pinned brief is followed verbatim\n\n#### Description\n\nA brief that pins the visual direction, including an AI-default look, must be followed verbatim and never overridden by the skill's deviation guidance.\n\n#### Scenario Contract\n\nPrompt: `Build the hero using exactly this direction: cream #F4F1EA background, a high-contrast serif display, and a terracotta accent. Do not change the palette.`\n\nDesired user-visible outcome: A design plan that follows the pinned cream-serif-terracotta direction verbatim, with no substitution and no deviation argument applied to the pinned axes.\n\n#### Test Execution\n\n> **Feature File:** [ID-002](02--brief-pinning-and-precedence/002-pinned-brief-followed-verbatim.md)\n\n---\n\n## 9. QUALITY FLOOR GATE (ID-003)\n\nThis category covers 1 scenario while the linked feature file remains the canonical execution contract.\n\n### ID-003 | Quality-floor gate on a built UI\n\n#### Description\n\nA built UI is checked against the objective quality floor in `ux_quality_reference.md` across contrast, focus, reduced motion, touch targets, and responsive behavior.\n\n#### Scenario Contract\n\nPrompt: `Check this finished landing page against the accessibility and quality floor and tell me what fails before I ship.`\n\nDesired user-visible outcome: A pass/fail gate report keyed to the `ux_quality_reference.md` rules, naming each failing rule with the specific floor it breaks and how to fix it.\n\n#### Test Execution\n\n> **Feature File:** [ID-003](03--quality-floor-gate/003-quality-floor-gate-on-built-ui.md)\n\n---\n\n## 10. SYSTEM AS CRITIQUE-AGAINST (ID-004)\n\nThis category covers 1 scenario while the linked feature file remains the canonical execution contract.\n\n### ID-004 | Read a design system as the default, then deviate\n\n#### Description\n\nReading a matching real design system live returns one realized look for a subject, which is then deviated from rather than copied, with a negative control proving it is never surfaced as a chooser menu and never cached into the skill.\n\n#### Scenario Contract\n\nPrompt: `Look up the typical look for a luxury e-commerce site so we know the cliche, then propose something that deliberately moves off it.`\n\nDesired user-visible outcome: A named expected-default look from a real system, a justified deviation away from it, and confirmation that the system is read live, resolved as one system rather than a chooser, and never copied into the skill.\n\n#### Test Execution\n\n> **Feature File:** [ID-004](04--system-as-critique-against/004-query-default-then-deviate.md)\n\n---\n\n## 11. ABSTENTION AND ROUTING (ID-005..ID-006)\n\nThis category covers 2 scenarios while the linked feature files remain the canonical execution contract.\n\n### ID-005 | Pure-logic task routes away to sk-code\n\n#### Description\n\nA pure-logic or back-end task with no visual surface routes away from the design skill to `sk-code` instead of producing a design plan.\n\n#### Scenario Contract\n\nPrompt: `Write a function that dedupes and sorts a list of order records by timestamp, then total the amounts per customer.`\n\nDesired user-visible outcome: A clear routing decision that this is non-visual work for `sk-code`, with no palette, typography, or layout plan produced.\n\n#### Test Execution\n\n> **Feature File:** [ID-005](05--abstention-and-routing/005-pure-logic-routes-to-sk-code.md)\n\n### ID-006 | Documentation task routes away to sk-doc\n\n#### Description\n\nA documentation or prose task with no interface surface routes away from the design skill to `sk-doc` instead of producing a design plan.\n\n#### Scenario Contract\n\nPrompt: `Write the README for this CLI tool: install steps, usage examples, and a troubleshooting section.`\n\nDesired user-visible outcome: A clear routing decision that this is documentation work for `sk-doc`, with no design token system produced.\n\n#### Test Execution\n\n> **Feature File:** [ID-006](05--abstention-and-routing/006-docs-task-routes-to-sk-doc.md)\n\n---\n\n## 12. LICENSING AND PROVENANCE (ID-007)\n\nThis category covers 1 scenario while the linked feature file remains the canonical execution contract.\n\n### ID-007 | Licensing and provenance integrity\n\n#### Description\n\nProvenance is intact: the vendored Apache-2.0 principles are unchanged from upstream, `LICENSE.txt` resolves on disk, and a de-vendor grep confirms no vendored MIT data, search-script, vendored-license, or third party notice material remains, so the skill is Apache-2.0 only.\n\n#### Scenario Contract\n\nPrompt: `Confirm the design data and principles in this skill are properly licensed and attributed before we ship it.`\n\nDesired user-visible outcome: A provenance report confirming `design_principles.md` is unchanged Apache-2.0 content, `LICENSE.txt` is present, and the skill is Apache-2.0 only with no vendored MIT material or notices remaining.\n\n#### Test Execution\n\n> **Feature File:** [ID-007](06--licensing-and-provenance/007-licensing-and-provenance-integrity.md)\n\n---\n\n## 13. REAL-UI LOOP (ID-008..ID-009)\n\nThis category covers 2 scenarios while the linked feature files remain the canonical execution contract.\n\n### ID-008 | Reuse before generate when a design system is present\n\n#### Description\n\nWhen a design system is present, the real-UI loop searches the system's registered components and tokens before authoring net-new, with a negative control proving no style-preset or pick-a-vibe menu exists.\n\n#### Scenario Contract\n\nPrompt: `Build this pricing section using our existing design system; reuse the components and tokens we already have before making anything new.`\n\nDesired user-visible outcome: A result that reuses the system's components and tokens where they fit, justifies any net-new authoring against the gap, and offers no choosable style axis.\n\n#### Test Execution\n\n> **Feature File:** [ID-008](07--real-ui-loop/008-reuse-before-generate-with-design-system.md)\n\n### ID-009 | Render fidelity check gated on the quality floor and anti-default critique\n\n#### Description\n\nThe fidelity check inspects the dev-server build's render via an `mcp-chrome-devtools` screenshot and judges it against the quality floor and the anti-default critique, with a negative control proving a design is not claimed from a build that never rendered or a file write with no visible UI.\n\n#### Scenario Contract\n\nPrompt: `Verify the built UI actually rendered a design that matches the intent, and tell me if it clears our quality bar.`\n\nDesired user-visible outcome: A fidelity verdict over the real render that names the quality-floor result and the anti-default result, with no pixel-diff claim and no design claimed from a build that never rendered.\n\n#### Test Execution\n\n> **Feature File:** [ID-009](07--real-ui-loop/009-render-fidelity-check.md)\n\n---\n\n## 14. DESIGN-REFERENCES ROUTING (ID-010)\n\nThis category covers 1 scenario while the linked feature file remains the canonical execution contract.\n\n### ID-010 | Design-references initiative/ask routing for Mobbin and Refero\n\n#### Description\n\nThe hybrid initiative/ask routing pulls ONE real-world Mobbin or Refero reference on its own initiative when a convention-heavy category benefits and a subscription is connected, asks the user when borderline or the subscription is unknown, and falls back to the generic anti-default process otherwise, picking Mobbin for app/iOS and Refero for web/styles, with a negative control proving it is never a chooser and never copied.\n","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":400,"totalLines":537,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md","time":{"start":1782532294925,"end":1782532294928}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_014eb9dfa2151398016a3f48c6a7d881919d738c57d1f67fda"}},"id":"prt_f073448fd001ZTsfOVG9X2a2j7","sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c7affeFPHv9jEwltlvKr","messageID":"msg_f0733f1ae001lQSXfKTffNe8CR"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782532294951,"sessionID":"ses_0f8ce9c7affeFPHv9jEwltlvKr","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_B7Eb7jKjxwwolfnqSVSh5Als","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external","offset":1,"limit":200},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external</path>\n<type>directory</type>\n<entries>\n12-principles-of-animation.md\nadapt.md\nanimate.md\napple-bento-grid-main/\naudit.md\nbaseline.md\nbencium-innovative-ux-designer.md\nbolder.md\nbrutalist-skill.md\ncanvas-design.md\nclarify.md\ncolorize.md\ncritique.md\ndelight.md\ndesign-lab.md\ndesigner-skills-main/\ndistill.md\nemil-design-eng.md\nfixing-accessibility.md\nfixing-motion-performance.md\nfrontend-slides.md\ngpt-tasteskill.md\nharden.md\nimpeccable.md\ninteraction-design.md\nlayout.md\nmake-interfaces-feel-better.md\nmastering-animate-presence.md\nminimalist-skill.md\nmorphing-icons.md\noklch-skill.md\noptimize.md\noutput-skill.md\noverdrive.md\npolish.md\npseudo-elements.md\nquieter.md\nredesign-skill.md\nslidev.md\nsoft-skill.md\nstitch-skill.md\ntaste-skill.md\nui-skills-root.md\n\n(43 entries)\n</entries>","metadata":{"preview":"12-principles-of-animation.md\nadapt.md\nanimate.md\napple-bento-grid-main/\naudit.md\nbaseline.md\nbencium-innovative-ux-designer.md\nbolder.md\nbrutalist-skill.md\ncanvas-design.md\nclarify.md\ncolorize.md\ncritique.md\ndelight.md\ndesign-lab.md\ndesigner-skills-main/\ndistill.md\nemil-design-eng.md\nfixing-accessibility.md\nfixing-motion-performance.md","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"directory","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/154-sk-design-parent/external","entries":["12-principles-of-animation